Just for the proper closure of this issue. I figured out a way around this.
1. Open native(usual) terminal
2. Run:
```
CONDA_SUBDIR=osx-64 conda create -n <env_name> python=3.9
conda activate <env_name>
conda config --env --set subdir osx-64
```
3. Run `pip install -U turicreate` and you're done.

import turicreate as tc

sa = sf['image']
```

I'm not really understanding the table you've shared. How does your side information contain both a person id and a product id? I would expect two separate SFrames: one with the side information for persons and one with the side information for products.

> And one clarifying question: What is the purpose of the stateInLength variable and how do I chose the correct value for it considering my data sets?
>
> static let stateInLength = 400 // Val added

Yeah, this is a bit opaque. It's basically the amount of state the model hold between predictions. A smaller number means the model hold less state. A larger number mean the model holds more state.

This is an example of a hyper parameter that can be tuned. There is no way to know the best value without experimenting. Build several different models with different values for this hyper parameter. Then evaluate each using a test set.

original_comment:
SFrame and SArray are lazily evaluated. If it's taking a long time for `sum` to return, that's probably because `sum` is forcing evaluation of other things which haven't actually been computed yet. 

You can force thing to be evaluated by calling `materialize()`. Try calling `products.materialize()`, right before calling sum. I would expect the `materialize` call to take almost all of the ~9 seconds you're seeing. Then `sum` should return very quickly.

original_comment:
This is a TensorFlow issue. On Linux (and older versions of macOS) TuriCreate uses TensorFlow to generate the deep feature.  

To reproduce this issue without TuriCreate, first [download the keras model](https://docs-assets.developer.apple.com/turicreate/models/VGGishFeatureEmbedding-v1.h5). Then run:
```python
from tensorflow import keras
import numpy as np

m = keras.models.load_model('./VGGishFeatureEmbedding-v1.h5')
x = np.ones((96, 64, 1))
m.predict([[x]])
```
The above code work with TensorFlow version `2.1.3` but stops working with `2.2.0`.

@ananasn - I recommend creating a [TensorFlow issue](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/new?assignees=&labels=type%3Abug&template=00-bug-issue.md) with the above information. Please share a link to that issue here. I'll leave this issue open.

This issue was created before 6.0. So things may have changed, but it looks like the skipping of rows is by design.

original_comment:
Adding some context since @malcolmgreaves mentioned the poetry thread. For tools like poetry, because we do dependency resolution ahead of time, we rely on metadata first (when available). This means that the information served from PyPI is used first. If one is not available, we do inspect the platform wheels to identify the metadata.

Typically, in a best practice scenario, one would expect [PEP 508 Environment Markers](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0508/#environment-markers) to be relied upon to provide consistent metadata across all wheels. Unfortunately, setuptool based concention has most often been to rely upon conditional logic within `setup.py`, which leads us to the current situation of partial metadata.

From a personaly opinion perspective, it would be great if projects did this the best they can. For example your `install_requires` and `extras_require` could be something like this.

```py
install_requires = [
    "Pillow>=5.2.0",
    "PrettyTable==0.7.2",
    "decorator>=4.0.9",
    "numpy>=1.19.2,<2.0.0",
    "pandas>=0.23.2",
    "requests>=2.9.1",
    "resampy==0.2.1",
    "scipy>=1.1.0",
    "six>=1.10.0",
]

extras_require = {
    ':python_version < "3.8"': ["coremltools==3.3"],
    ':python_version >= "2.7" and python_version < "2.8" or python_version >= "3.5" and python_version < "3.6"': [
        "llvmlite==0.31.0"
    ],
    ':python_version >= "3.8.0" and python_version < "4.0.0"': ["coremltools==4.0b3"],
    ':sys_platform != "darwin"': [
        "tensorflow>=2.0.0,<2.1.0",
        "tensorflow>=2.0.0",
        "numba<0.51.0",
    ],
    ':sys_platform == "darwin"': ["tensorflow>=2.0.0"],
}
```

The generated `PKG-INFO` will look something like this.
```
Requires-Dist: Pillow (>=5.2.0)
Requires-Dist: PrettyTable (==0.7.2)
Requires-Dist: coremltools (==3.3); python_version < "3.8"
Requires-Dist: coremltools (==4.0b3); python_version >= "3.8.0" and python_version < "4.0.0"
Requires-Dist: decorator (>=4.0.9)
Requires-Dist: llvmlite (==0.31.0); python_version >= "2.7" and python_version < "2.8" or python_version >= "3.5" and python_version < "3.6"
Requires-Dist: numba (<0.51.0); sys_platform != "darwin"
Requires-Dist: numpy (>=1.19.2,<2.0.0)
Requires-Dist: pandas (>=0.23.2)
Requires-Dist: requests (>=2.9.1)
Requires-Dist: resampy (==0.2.1)
Requires-Dist: scipy (>=1.1.0)
Requires-Dist: six (>=1.10.0)
Requires-Dist: tensorflow (>=2.0.0); sys_platform != "darwin"
Requires-Dist: tensorflow (>=2.0.0); sys_platform == "darwin"
Requires-Dist: tensorflow (>=2.0.0,<2.1.0); sys_platform != "darwin"
```

You can also just put this into your `install_requires`.

This was generated from the following. Obviously, I am not familiar with this project or how the dependencies are used. But hopefully this is useful.

```toml
[tool.poetry.dependencies]
python = "^3.8"
decorator = ">=4.0.9"
numpy = "^1.19.2"
pandas = ">=0.23.2"
Pillow = ">=5.2.0"
PrettyTable = "0.7.2"
resampy = "0.2.1"
requests = ">=2.9.1"
scipy = ">=1.1.0"
six = ">=1.10.0"
llvmlite = { version = "0.31.0", python = "~2.7 || ~3.5" }
coremltools = [
    { version = "4.0b3", python = "^3.8.0" },
    { version = "3.3", python = "<3.8" }
]
tensorflow = [
    { version = ">=2.0.0", markers = "sys_platform == 'darwin'" },
    { version = ">=2.0.0,<2.1.0",  python = "~2.7 || <3.8", markers = "sys_platform != 'darwin'" },
    { version = ">=2.0.0",  python = "^3.8.0", markers = "sys_platform != 'darwin'" }
]
numba = { version = "<0.51.0", markers = "sys_platform != 'darwin'" }
```

original_comment:
Much of that memory is probably just the images themselves. Try first extracting the deep features from the images. Then before creating the model, allow the memory for those images to be garbage collected.

Also try using a squeezenet backed model, rather than the resnet default. It will have smaller deep features and also a smaller neural network.

If your SFrame is called `sf` and your image column is called `image`, you would want to do the following:
```python
sf['deep_features'] = tc.image_analysis.get_deep_features(sf['image'], model_name="squeezenet_v1.1")
del sf['image']    # allow images to be garbage collected
model = tc.image_similarity.create(sf, feature='deep_features', model="squeezenet_v1.1")
```

Ah I think I've found out what was wrong. The `user_id` field provided in the `items` field has to be the same type as the one provided during training. In this case, mine was supposed to be `str` instead of `int`. However, the `user_id` provided in the `users` field does not seem to care the type. Is this intended?

```python
user_query = turicreate.SFrame({'user_id':['33551']}) #str here
restricted_df = turicreate.SFrame({'user_id':[33551], "item_id":['s3rc']}) #int here
recommendations = model.recommend(users=user_query, k=10, items=restricted_df, diversity=1)
# no results

user_query = turicreate.SFrame({'user_id':['33551']}) # user_id as str here
restricted_df = turicreate.SFrame({'user_id':['33551'], "item_id":['s3rc']}) # user_id as str here
recommendations = model.recommend(users=user_query, k=10, items=restricted_df, diversity=1)
# results given

user_query = turicreate.SFrame({'user_id':[33551]}) #int here
restricted_df = turicreate.SFrame({'user_id':['33551'], "item_id":['s3rc']}) # user_id as str here
recommendations = model.recommend(users=user_query, k=10, items=restricted_df, diversity=1)
# results given
```

@zhunhung - Thanks for letting me know it's the `ranking_factorization_recommender`. It would be super helpful if you could give a minimal reproduction example, i.e. one that uses some stubbed out data that is just a few rows.

According to [the documentation](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/api/generated/turicreate.recommender.ranking_factorization_recommender.RankingFactorizationRecommender.recommend.html#turicreate.recommender.ranking_factorization_recommender.RankingFactorizationRecommender.recommend) for the `items` parameter this should work:
```
Restricts the items from which recommendations can be made. If items is an SArray, list, or SFrame with a single column, only items from the given set will be recommended. This can be used, for example, to restrict the recommendations to items within a particular category or genre. If items is an SFrame with user ID and item ID columns, then the item restriction is specialized to each user. For example, if items contains 3 rows with user U1 ‚Äì (U1, I1), (U1, I2), and (U1, I3) ‚Äì then the recommendations for user U1 are chosen from items I1, I2, and I3. By default, recommendations are made from all items present when the model was trained.
```

Does it work if the SFrame only has one column? In other words, does the following work?
```python
restricted_df = turicreate.SFrame({"item_id":[1]})
results = recommender.recommend(users=users, items=restricted_df)
```

Also what about an SArray? Does the following work?
```python
restricted_df = turicreate.SArray([1])
results = recommender.recommend(users=users, items=restricted_df)
``

original_comment:
To use S3 - first set your AWS credentials in your environment. I usually execute the following system command before starting my Python session:
```
export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=XXXX
export AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=XXXX
```
Of course replace `XXXX` with your values.

Once you've started Python and imported turicreate. You'll probably want to set `TURI_S3_ENDPOINT` and `TURI_S3_REGION` via [turicreate.config.set_runtime_config](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/api/generated/turicreate.config.set_runtime_config.html#turicreate.config.set_runtime_config).

Then all you should need to do is call `my_model.save("s3:\\<bucket_name>\<key>")`.

----------

It sounds like you already understand the copying approach I mentioned; yes, you'll want to copy the (.ini, .sidx, .bin , .0000) individual files. I would probably tar the entire directory and then just copy the tar file.

TuriCreate models are disk backed. So even if you can get all of the `model_loaded` variable copied to the cloud, it's still not going to work.

We do have built in S3 support, but it looks like you're using a different cloud provider.

If the model will only be used for inference and will run on an Apple device, you could export to CoreML and uploading that. 

I think your best option is just copying the saved model files to the cloud.

original_comment:
Yes, in general, I would recommend resizing images to something not too much bigger than the network's input size, which by default is 416 by 416. (You might want to go somewhat bigger, since each image can be randomly cropped each time it is used, before being resized to the network's input size.) This is something we've long talked about doing, but we would want to investigate any accuracy impact for different ranges of resizing before just doing this automatically.

This particular issue might be addressed by #3282, which would defer the image loading until later in the pipeline. The SFrame manipulations would then be manipulating image paths, not full images.

original_comment:
The Python 2.7 issue was fixed by the [last commit](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/pull/3253/commits/7147ab859f94497777964036e007951271ad376e).

Slow LSTM runtime in Keras seems to be a common issue. It **seems** our issue is that we have to use a pure-TensorFlow LSTM rather than a cuDNN-based LSTM. From [the Keras documentation](https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/keras/layers/LSTM):
```
Based on available runtime hardware and constraints, this layer will choose different
implementations (cuDNN-based or pure-TensorFlow) to maximize the performance.
If a GPU is available and all the arguments to the layer meet the requirement of the
CuDNN kernel (see below for details), the layer will use a fast cuDNN implementation.

The requirements to use the cuDNN implementation are:

activation == tanh
recurrent_activation == sigmoid
recurrent_dropout == 0
unroll is False
use_bias is True
Inputs are not masked or strictly right padded.
```
Our usage satisfies all of those requirements, except we're using `use_bias=False`. Using a bias here would probably make things a lot faster. However, if we use a bias, then additional parameters will need to be serialized when saving a model. This would prevent models trained in TuriCreate 6.4+ from being loaded in an earlier version of TuriCreate.

Although the percentage increase is significant, the total time is still small.
processed_comment: python issue fixed last commit slow common issue issue use rather documentation based available hardware layer choose different maximize performance available layer meet requirement kernel see layer use fast implementation use implementation activation tanh sigmoid unroll false true masked strictly right usage except bias would probably make lot faster however use bias additional need saving model would prevent trained loaded version although percentage increase significant total time still small

original_comment:
@tagy - A neural network returns fixed number of predictions which are first filtered by the confidence threshold and then only the boxes left after this filtering with confidence threshold are subjected to Non Maximum Suppression (NMS). Essentially setting higher threshold would affect what the input to Non maximum suppression. So depending on how different your input to NMS is based on your threshold, the output of the NMS could vary. 

I think adding more data for the classes which are similar looking as well as more negative data would be great.

Thanks @power76 for the repro code! Glad that your model training completed. <strike>Before we investigate the slowness from iteration 771 to 772, could you share which version of Turi Create and which version of Python you are using?</strike>

If you're using Turi Create 6.0+, as you correctly observed, looking at https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/src/toolkits/object_detection/od_data_iterator.cpp#L392-L411, we shuffle the data at the end of an epoch.

While we do have a `shuffle` method on the SFrame (#3060), we haven't plumbed it through to the Object Detector because of its lack of reproducibility (because of its dependence on `groupby` which doesn't take a seed). We are tracking this in #3122 . I'll close this issue for now since the underlying issue here is the shuffling, the fix to which is resolving #3122  and replacing the code [here](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/src/toolkits/object_detection/od_data_iterator.cpp#L392-L411).

Feel free to reopen the issue if you have any further questions about using the One Shot Object Detector or the Object Detector!

original_comment:
I think there are several reasons someone might choose to use TuriCreate rather than another tool. Below are what I see as the three largest reasons. 

1 - **Ease of use**. Turi Create is designed to simplify the development of custom machine learning models. It aims be the easiest way to add Machine Learning to your app. Hopefully in as few as five lines of code. Our [Task Focused Toolkits](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/applications/) are particularly easy to use. Our lower level toolkits also try to do as much as possible for you. For example one hot encoding and dictionary vectorization are handled for you by TuriCreate. With most other tools you need to do this yourself.

2 - **Work with large dataset on your laptop**. TuriCreate make wide use of [SFrames](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/api/generated/turicreate.SFrame.html), a tabular dataframe which is disk backed, so it scales to "Big data". Our toolkits are built on top of SFrame which mean you can create machine learning models using a dataset larger than the size of your RAM.

3 - **Export to Core ML**. Most models created by TuriCreate can be exported to [Core ML](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/coreml); you can easily deploy most TuriCreate models to any Apple device.

@theobouwman - I'm going to close this, but let me know if you have any additional specific questions.

original_comment:
Hello @boaloysius, 

The scores on the leaves of each tree are added together, then transformed through a sigmoid function, i.e. `1 / (1 + exp(-x) )`.  This sigmoid function maps a score of 0 to probability 0.5 and all the results are between 0 and 1. 

Now, the probability threshold is set to 0.5, though the "probability" can be affected during training by adjusting the class weights at training time, so in that sense it's not really a true probability as the training can be biased one way or the other.  To do your own PR curve, though, you can have the predict() function output the raw probabilities instead of just a class prediction and threshold it yourself.

original_comment:
Here is a function I wrote to do cross validation:

```python 
def get_cross_validation_generator(sf, k):
    '''
    Parameters
    ----------
    sf : SFrame
        The SFrame on which to do cross validation

    k : int
        The number of folds

    Returns
    -------
    out : generator
        The generator yields a tuple with two members. The first
        member of the tuple is the train set SFrame. The second member
        is the test set.
    '''
    sf = sf.shuffle()
    fold_size = len(sf) // k

    for i in range(k-1):
        test_set_start = i * fold_size
        test_set_end = (i+1) * fold_size

        cur_test = sf[test_set_start:test_set_end]
        cur_train = sf[:test_set_start] + sf[test_set_end:]

        yield cur_train, cur_test

    # Add any left over portion to the final test set
    final_divide = (k-1) * fold_size
    yield sf[:final_divide], sf[final_divide:]
```

Here is an example of using it:
```python
# Test get_cross_validation_generator
import turicreate as tc
sf = tc.SFrame({'a': range(11)})
for train, test in get_fold(sf, 5):
    print(train)
    print(test)
    print("\n\n")
```

original_comment: Numpy appears to do some sort of linear smoothing between -4 and -1, which is not standard but common.  Technically (in statistics) the quantile of an empirical distribution like this can be anywhere in between the two values given.  Typically, one of those values is returned as the quantile.  In this case, [-100, -4, -1, 10] would mean that anything in [-4, -1] is valid as a numerical quantile.  However, the median almost always returns value that is present in the dataset, which is what we do here, returning -1.  So our result is correct.

Turicreate requires `libnsl` shared object which used to come bundled with `glibc` in earlier versions of fedora but turns out it got discontinued for some reason.

Installed `libnsl` with command:
`sudo dnf install libnsl`
 and now `turicreate` is working.

What I didn't understand that pip should've checked `libnsl` dependency before installing but I did not get any error during installation.

[The code I shared previously](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/issues/745#issuecomment-408253208) is not going to work when `approx = False`. It turns out we can not use `tc.aggregate.QUANTILE` if we want exact answers. 

The docstring for `tc.aggregate.QUANTILE` contains this surprising information:
```
The returned quantiles are guaranteed to have 0.5% accuracy. That is to say,
if the requested quantile is 0.50, the resultant quantile value may be
between 0.495 and 0.505 of the true quantile.
```

original_comment: I've suggested in #3060 that irreproducible model is not really useful for model development. I have worked on optimizing `groupby` #2210 before and I think the overall sort is a bucket sort instead of merge sort on entire set since each hash bucket is relatively sorted (#2210). What we need to do is to do something similar to `stable sort`, where we can provide an extra index column to track the original order and feed it into `groupby` together. After the `groupby`, we should be able to reconstruct their original relative order __within__ the bucket. The big O can be `n + B*log(n/B)`, where B is the bucket number in the hash table used by `groupby`.

original_comment:
> Aside: is there any prospect of controlling this behavior with a random seed? What random seed does it use?

In order to get an O(n) running time without random access, we had to rely on `groupby` which doesn't have a seed option. It sounds like adding that functionality to `groupby` isn't really possible.

The idea of having a random seed for shuffle is related to #3122. There I was planning on using the SFrame shuffle only if the user did not pass a random seed to `tc.object_detection.create`. If the user did pass in a random seed, the current sort based shuffle functionality would be used. 

Something I've considered doing instead is moving that sort based shuffle functionality from the object detector into SFrame shuffle. The end result would be that SArray/SFrame shuffle would have a seed option; shuffle would run in O(n) time if no seed is given and O(n log n) if a seed is given. This shouldn't add too much additional work to #3122. Let me know if you think that is worth doing.

original_comment:
I monkey patched SFrames with this:

```
import turicreate as tc
from turicreate._cython.context import debug_trace as cython_context

def replace_column(self, data, column_name=""):
    if not isinstance(column_name, str):
        raise TypeError("Invalid column name: must be str")

    ret = self.copy()

    with cython_context():
        ret.__proxy__.add_column(data.__proxy__, f"{column_name}_tmp")
        ret.__proxy__.remove_column(self.column_names().index(column_name))
        ret.__proxy__.set_column_name(ret.column_names().index(f"{column_name}_tmp"), column_name)
    
    ret._cache = None
    
    return ret

tc.SFrame.replace_column = replace_column
```

Seems to work

original_comment:
@NeerajKomuravalli - Sorry for the delay. I wanted to discuss this matter with my manager before responding. We think having one function under `tc.image_analysis` would be best.

I think it should look like `tc.image_analysis.get_deep_features(images, model_name)`
Where `images` is an SArray of images and `model_name` is a string.

Below is a list of things that will should to be done. There is likely more needed but this should be most of it.

# Get Deep Features
- [ ] Create `tc.image_analysis.get_deep_features` and write the docstring
- [ ] Parameter checking for `tc.image_analysis.get_deep_features`. Make sure `images` is a non-empty SArray of images. Make sure `model_name` is a string with one of the three allowed values (note ‚ÄúVisionFeaturePrint_Scene‚Äù is only allowed on certain macOS version -- see existing code). If any of the parameter aren't right the user should get an informative error message. 
- [ ] Implement `tc.image_analysis.get_deep_features`. You should be able to just use the existing code from either the image classifier or image similarity.

# Image Classifier
- [ ] Modify code to check if the input are deep features. We already do [something similar for the sound classifier](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/ccc5eb9d53c9dbf58d111fd81a9458b3cc6fd4d4/src/python/turicreate/toolkits/sound_classifier/sound_classifier.py#L365). Creating a helper function here would probably be good so you can also use it for image similarity too.
- [ ] If deep features are not passed in, the code should just use `tc.image_analysis.get_deep_features` to get the deep features. This is so we don't have duplicated code. 
- [ ] Update the docstring.
- [ ] Write image classifier unit tests for this new functionality.

# Image Similarity
- [ ] Modify code to check if the input are deep features. 
- [ ] If deep features are not passed in, the code should use tc.image_analysis.get_deep_features`. 
- [ ] Update the docstring.
- [ ] Write unit tests for this new functionality.

Let me know if you have any questions. Feel free to put up a work in progress pull request at any point, if you would like feedback.

original_comment:
It turns out that the most robust thing to do is not to use TensorFlow's random number generation at all. By generating a batch-specific seed in C++, we can use numpy for all the Python-side RNG, seeded by the C++ seed.

This has some advantages over the approach from #2892:
1. Sampling a numpy random number table during image augmentation initialization implies that we're using the same results for each iteration. For example, if the first image of the first batch skips horizontal flip, then the first image of every batch will skip horizontal flip.
2. Relying on TF RNG, which is scoped to sessions, will make it difficult to support resuming from a checkpoint with the correct semantics.

original_comment:
@navanchauhan - you should be able to manually classify a single example.

SVM classifiers work by calculating a "margin" value, which is the distance of the example from the hyperplane.

Take a look at [the SVM page of our User Guide](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/supervised-learning/svm.html) for more information here. Also you can get the margin value from an `svm_classifer` by passing `output_type="margin"` to the `predict` function - see the [API documentation](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/api/generated/turicreate.svm_classifier.SVMClassifier.predict.html#turicreate.svm_classifier.SVMClassifier.predict).

If this margin value is greater than or equal to zero, one class is predicted, else the other class is predicted.

If both `a` and `b` are numerical values, it's easy to calculate the margin. Simply multiple the value of `a` and `b` with their corresponding coefficient, then add the intercept. [Here](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/8700c39388c4784a79ac8a4f763ac1346ad9cf83/src/toolkits/supervised_learning/linear_svm.cpp#L260) is our code for doing this.

Let me know if you have any more questions.

original_comment:
I don't have a fix for this issue but I've done a lot more debugging and want to give an update. The segfault is caused by just importing TensorFlow 2.1.0 (on Linux) from inside of pybind. 

When TensorFlow is loaded, it lazily loads several of its top level modules. The issue seems to be related to this lazily loading mechanism. After lazy loading for its first module is setup, `sys.modules` seems to be in a bad state. After lazy loading for the second module is setup, just accessing `sys.modules` results in a segfault.

TensorFlow 2.1.0 (on Linux) loads just fine outside of pybind.

original_comment:
groupby concat is inherently really memory intensive as it essentially ends up storing the lists of values in the intermediate parts in memory.  This is especially true if there are a lot of common values.  For instance, if one value grouped on contains 50% of values in your dataset, 50% of your data gets dumped into one in-memory list.  Unfortunately, it's really hard to get around this in the general case at the lower level.

What's your use case for using concat?  There may be other ways around it.

original_comment:
> this is using **pull** model, instead of **push** model.
> 
> Since there's no **mailbox** and **watermark** concept, it's hard for a publisher to send one data to many subscribers (unless each buffered task queue for each subscriber). All subscribers consume the publisher.
> 
> I kind of understand why `publisher` calls `subscribe` on `subscriber`. `subscriber` is the initiator of this dataflow, instead of `publisher`. It's like `publisher` subscribes **requests** from `subscriber`.

Yes, good point. Honestly, I suspect most clients of Apple's Combine framework do use a push model, by requesting unlimited demand from a root publisher that is ultimately event-based. (To respond to e.g. user interaction on a UI widget or a notification).

In our case, we want to use the back-pressure mechanism built into Combine to instead use a pull model, where the iterator only emits another batch on demand.

Thanks for taking a close look at all of this!

> This comment is only regarding the OD files (object_detector, od_model and od_darket_yolo_model)
> The `object_detector` is the most high level file which takes out all of the model specific pieces.

> The `od_darket_yolo_model` (lowest level file) derives from the pieces from `od_model` and implements exactly how darknet-yolo needs the implementation to be. So if we want to ever add another model backend for OD, we would need to only add a file like `od_darknet_yolo_model`. Is this right?

I see three levels here:

1. The `model_backend` implementation, which is platform-specific and only knows about one batch at a time: how to update model parameters given one batch of data
2. The new `Model` and `DarknetYOLOModel` classes, which know about training pipelines that combine data, augmentation, and a model backend
3. The `object_detector` class, which talks to Python and knows about save/load and SFrame, etc.

When we add new model architectures, we'll probably want a new `model_backend` and `Model` subclass for each, but ideally we should need few changes elsewhere

original_comment:
High-level overview of changes: defined a new interface in `od_model.hpp` meant to abstract over various model architectures. The code in that file deals with what should be shared among architectures: how we process (and augment) the data.

Then `od_darknet_yolo_model.hpp` declares code that is specific to the current `darknet-yolo` model. Much of this code is moved from `object_detector.cpp`, which way too strongly assumed one specific model.

Finally, `object_detector.cpp` adopts the new Combine-like framework. The class itself no longer maintains direct references to all the dependencies, just to the "outlets" of the training pipeline. This also moves us away from using `nn_spec_` as the source of truth for a model (since this was out of date anyway the moment we train anything). Instead, there's an explicit `Checkpoint` type that represents what we need to serialize, which also handily defines the minimum required to instantiate a backend.

@hoytak Sorry for the late reply. Really appreciate your good suggestion. It looks quite "different" somehow but very interesting. We actually tried it. Here are the findings and thoughts:

1. Yes, indeed, the context info now can be incorporated in this way, but it's more like viewing it as a common classification problem and it loses the power of efficiently modeling 2-order or higher order feature interactions like Collaborative Filtering/ Factorization Machine does. It's actually totally fine , just making me curious if it'll be better using vanilla Factorization Machines.

2. For the first point you make, we did try your suggestion by modeling user with the list of his purchased items. But we didn't find any performance improvement compared to simply modeling user with a categorical variable. The only advantage I can see is it can help reduce the number of coefficients. original_comment:
It can be incorporated with this model, but the issue is that the optimization to train it can be extremely hard and the resulting model can be extremely finicky.  We could never get it working reliably in production -- it was way too sensitive.  

In your case, you're lucky with having only 60 items. I would actually treat this as a multiclass classification problem.  Set the problem up like this:

For each observation, have as features: 
1. A binary vector of 0s and 1s indicating which items other than the observed item that the user interacted with.  In TC, this can be done as a categorical list of strings e.g. ["item1", "item5", "item45"] . If there are ratings there, use a dictionary instead.  This is how the user data is encoded. 
2. All the relevant side information. 
3. The target class would be the item the user interacted with. 

I would trial run this with logistic_classifier, then the boosted_trees_classifier would give you the best accuracy. 

Then, on prediction, get the probability_vector type output, zero out all the items the user has interacted with, and rank recommendations by probability.

The reason behind changing single quotes to double quotes (cited from pep8):

In Python, **single-quoted strings and double-quoted strings are the same**. This PEP does not make a recommendation for this. Pick a rule and stick to it.

When a string contains single or double quote characters, however, **use the other one to avoid backslashes in the string**. It improves readability.

**For triple-quoted strings, always use double quote characters to be consistent with the docstring convention in PEP 257.**

> @MatthewWaller Can you share the exact pre-processing you did on the dataset just to make sure we can repro exactly what you did.

Sure thing:

First there is this Voice Activity Detection class to drop silences
```

class VoiceActivityDetection:

    def __init__(self):
        self.__step = 10
        self.__buffer_size = 10
        self.__buffer = numpy.array([],dtype=numpy.int16)
        self.__out_buffer = numpy.array([],dtype=numpy.int16)
        self.__n = 0
        self.__VADthd = 0.
        self.__VADn = 0.
        self.__silence_counter = 0

    # Voice Activity Detection
    # Adaptive threshold
    def vad(self, _frame):
        frame = numpy.array(_frame) ** 2.
        result = True
        threshold = 0.1
        thd = numpy.min(frame) + numpy.ptp(frame) * threshold
        self.__VADthd = (self.__VADn * self.__VADthd + thd) / float(self.__VADn + 1.)
        self.__VADn += 1.

        if numpy.mean(frame) <= self.__VADthd:
            self.__silence_counter += 1
        else:
            self.__silence_counter = 0

        if self.__silence_counter > 20:
            result = False
        return result

    # Push new audio samples into the buffer.
    def add_samples(self, data):
        self.__buffer = numpy.append(self.__buffer, data)
        result = len(self.__buffer) >= self.__buffer_size
        # print('__buffer size %i'%self.__buffer.size)
        return result

    # Pull a portion of the buffer to process
    # (pulled samples are deleted after being
    # processed
    def get_frame(self):
        window = self.__buffer[:self.__buffer_size]
        self.__buffer = self.__buffer[self.__step:]
        # print('__buffer size %i'%self.__buffer.size)
        return window

    # Adds new audio samples to the internal
    # buffer and process them
    def process(self, data):
        if self.add_samples(data):
            while len(self.__buffer) >= self.__buffer_size:
                # Framing
                window = self.get_frame()
                # print('window size %i'%window.size)
                if self.vad(window):  # speech frame
                	self.__out_buffer = numpy.append(self.__out_buffer, window)
                # print('__out_buffer size %i'%self.__out_buffer.size)

    def get_voice_samples(self):
        return self.__out_buffer
```

Then a function we'll use to split the sample values into 1 second intervals
```
import itertools

def split_seq(iterable, size):
    it = iter(iterable)
    item = list(itertools.islice(it, size))
    while item:
        yield item
        item = list(itertools.islice(it, size))
```

@nickjong  @guihao-liang 
Random sampling:
We want to acquire the following two properties for random sampling:
1. Each sample in a mini-batch has different behaviors:
Our image augmenter creates an array with length of batch_size, and uses a session to run it.
```
#construct the graph
self.img_tf = [tf.placeholder(tf.float32, [None, None, 3]) for x in range(0, self.batch_size )]
self.ann_tf = [tf.placeholder(tf.float32, [None, 6]) for x in range(0, self.batch_size )]
self.resize_op_batch = []
for i in range(0, self.batch_size):
       aug_img_tf, aug_ann_tf = complete_augmenter(self.img_tf[i], self.ann_tf[i], (output_height, output_width))
       self.resize_op_batch.append([aug_img_tf, aug_ann_tf])

#get augmenter output
aug_output = self.session.run(self.resize_op_batch)
```
We expect each element in aug_output has different output, and this can be achieved by assigning different seeds for each sample.
For simplicity we can look at the following behavior when each operation is a simple `tf.random.uniform` operation
```
# fixed seed for each sample
opt_batch = [tf.random.uniform([],0,1,seed=0), tf.random.uniform([],0,1,seed=0), tf.random.uniform([],0,1,seed=0)]
with tf.Session() as session:
        print(session.run(opt_batch))
```
The code produces something like
```
[0.232, 0.232, 0.232]
```
This is not what we want since each element in a batch produces the same result.
So I first use the user-given seed to generate an random seed array with length of the batch size in the beginning, and then assign the seed to each element.
```
np.random.seed(random_seed)
self.random_seed = np.random.randint(low=0, high=2**32-1, size=self.batch_size)
for i in range(0, self.batch_size):
        aug_img_tf, aug_ann_tf = complete_augmenter(self.img_tf[i], self.ann_tf[i], output_height, output_width, self.random_seed[i])
        self.resize_op_batch.append([aug_img_tf, aug_ann_tf])
```
This ensure that each element has different behavior.

2. Each mini-batch produce different results.
Again for each iteration, we want to ensure we get different results. This can be achieved by create only one session and run the augmenter every single time using the session.

What the master doing now is that it basically creates a new session for each iteration,
which will produce the same result across all iterations, which is not good.
```
#construct the graph
self.opt_batch = []
batch_size = 3
for i in range(batch_size):
    self.opt_batch.append(tf.random.uniform([],0,1,seed=i))

#for each iteration a new session is created
#say we run 3 iterations
with tf.Session() as session:
   print(session.run(self.opt_batch)
with tf.Session() as session:
   print(session.run(self.opt_batch)
with tf.Session() as session:
   print(session.run(self.opt_batch)
```
This gets results like
```
[0.231, 0.456, 0.771]
[0.231, 0.456, 0.771]
[0.231, 0.456, 0.771]
```
which is not what we want.

So I change the code to have only one session, for each iteration we use the same session to run the graph
```
self.session = tf.Session()
print(self.session.run(self.opt_batch))
print(self.session.run(self.opt_batch))
print(self.session.run(self.opt_batch))
```
This produces
```
[0.231, 0.456, 0.771]
[0.561, 0.032, 0.112]
[0.345, 0.987, 0.321]
```
which is nice haha.

Reproducibility
In the image augmenter, we basically have two kinds of random operation:
(1)The first one is the four tensorflow operations:
`tf.image.random_hue`, `tf.image.random_brightness`, `tf.image.random_saturation`, and `tf.image.random_contrast`,
like what is reported in https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38469632/tensorflow-non-repeatable-results/40247201, `tf.set_random_set` at the graph level sadly is useless for some operations. And these four operations belong to this as I observed.
So I set the seed for each operation when constructing the graph.
```
tf.image.random_hue(image, max_delta=max_hue_adjust, seed=tf_seed)
...
tf.image.random_contrast(image, lower=np.exp(-log_con), upper=np.exp(log_con), seed=tf_seed)
```

(2) The second one is we use `np.random.uniform` throughout the code in `tf.numpy_function`.
Again, `tf.set_random_seed()` doesn't seem to work, and also `np.random.seed()` doesn't work either (I guess it is because the Numpy function is wrapped in tensorflow haha).
So I replaced every `numpy.random.uniform` in the code by a `tf.random.uniform` tensor.
```
#say if crop_augmenter has 5 np.random.uniform operations included
#I generate a random tensor random_nums with length 5 and pass it as an input
random_nums = tf.random.uniform([5], 0., 1., seed=seed_tf)
img_tf, ann_tf = tf.numpy_function(func=crop_augmenter, inp=[img_tf, ann_tf, random_nums], Tout=[tf.float32, tf.float32])
``` 

So by doing these change we could achieve both random sampling and reproducibility haha.

original_comment:
> > I doubt this pipelining will gain perf improv. When I profile tf, it spins a thread pool internally. If image feature extraction is dispatched to a certain thread in tf, what we need to do is to call tf again to let another thread run the new task.
> 
> I'm not sure I follow. The issue is that the GPU is waiting around while our code prepares the next batch. This is designed to keep both the GPU and CPU busy while all this is happening.

Ah! Thanks for the clarification! I see your point. 

(each line represents a thread)
I thought we can do, date parp in one step in parallel, and trigger G/Cpu process in parallel too,

|-prep-| ->  | -G/C- |
|-prep-| ->  | -G/C- |
...
|-prep-| ->  | -G/C- |

But in reality, we do data preparation batch by batch.

without pipeline, 
|-prep-|-G/C-|-prep-|-G/C-|-prep-|-G/C-|-prep-|-G/C-| ...

with the pipeline, (with assumption prep time is longer than G/Cpu processing time)
__________| -G/C- |  |-G/C- |   |-G/C- |
|-prep---|-prep---|-prep---|-prep---| ...

if G/Cpu processing time is longer than data prep time,
_____________________________| -G/C--------|  
____________________| -G/C--------|  
__________| -G/C--------|  
|-prep---|-prep---|-prep---|-prep---| ...

In this way, I think this pipelining is very valuable and can improve the overall throughput.

It's better to keep data preparation time less than G/Cpu processing time, then we can keep G/Cpu busy all the time.

original_comment:
That's somewhat expected behavior.  It's stored as a base-2 number, which doesn't map directly to base 10, so you get artifacts like that.  Those numbers are the closest ones in base 2 to the ones given.

In python:

In [8]: print("{0:.20f}".format(3.14))
3.14000000000000012434

However, it appears that those numbers are being converted through a 32 bit float type instead of a double, as it should be: 

In [13]: print("{0:.20f}".format(numpy.float32(3.14)))
3.14000010490417480469

In addition, we should respect python's default precision when printing numbers in sarray, possibly by using python's system internally. 

From https://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/floatingpoint.html: 

"In current versions, Python displays a value based on the shortest decimal fraction that rounds correctly back to the true binary value, resulting simply in ‚Äò0.1‚Äô."

> > > I agree we should give a warning rather than error here.

> > 
> > 
> > > I agree we should give a warning rather than error here.
> > > The more interesting question for: what should we do with examples in the test set that have previously unseen labels? Do we drop them? Does the model automatically get those wrong?
> > 
> > 
> > @TobyRoseman Great question. We drop those unseen labels, so it doesn't effect the evaluation.
> 
> This is part of my point. OD is not a classifier. Asking a detector to detect things in an image that happens to have objects that the detector wasn't trained on isn't inherently problematic, in the same way that (absent multi-label classification), it's inherently wrong to ask a classifier to classify an image whose one true label is one the classifier doesn't know about.
> 
> At present, OD evaluation works by computing average precision scores for each class on which the detector was trained. Suppose that you have a dataset of images annotated with cat and dog bounding boxes. It feels weird to me if you later go back, add additional annotations for "hamster" to a _test set_ and now get a warning.
> 
> I would argue that the right solution here is closer to including a note in the evaluation results. Perhaps the output of evaluation should simply note that the test data has classes that the detector cannot detect, and therefore there is no average precision score for those classes.

For my understanding, it would be nice to tell me that 'hamster' is not in training set so I can add 'hamster' to my training set in order to get better knowledge (under the assumption that cat images probably don't share deep features with hamsters). 

In practice, the test set serves a simulation as a production environment. True that production may have unseen data and the cycle to figure this out might be very long. That's why the training set could have unseen data over the test set.

Usually, people would promote the model to production if it works well in test set. The test set data distribution is actually very important. I think rarely people want to simulate the production with unseen data in the test set during the model training phase.

If the test set has unseen data over the training set, probably nothing I can do but add unseen data to the training set to start it over, which might be the handiest way to improve overall accuracy for the test set before promoting the model to production. Otherwise, the test performance might be poor and user doesn't have a clear clue to fix it.

The setup class will train the model and call tensorflow. It's unclear how RAM-hungry SF is.

```
def _get_data(feature, num_examples=100):
    from PIL import Image as _PIL_Image
    rs = np.random.RandomState(1234)
    def from_pil_image(pil_img, image_format='png'):
        # The above didn't work, so as a temporary fix write to temp files
        if image_format == 'raw':
            image = np.array(pil_img)
            FORMAT_RAW = 2
            return tc.Image(_image_data=image.tobytes(),
                            _width=image.shape[1],
                            _height=image.shape[0],
                            _channels=image.shape[2],
                            _format_enum=FORMAT_RAW,
                            _image_data_size=image.size)
        else:
            with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(mode='w+b', suffix='.' + image_format) as f:
                pil_img.save(f, format=image_format)
                return tc.Image(f.name)

    images = []
    FORMATS = ['png', 'jpeg', 'raw']
    for i in range(num_examples):
        # Randomly determine image size (should handle large and small)
        img_shape = tuple(rs.randint(100, 600, size=2)) + (3,)
        img = rs.randint(255, size=img_shape)

        pil_img = _PIL_Image.fromarray(img, mode='RGB')
        # Randomly select image format
        image_format = FORMATS[rs.randint(len(FORMATS))]
        images.append(from_pil_image(pil_img, image_format=image_format))

    data = tc.SFrame({
            feature: tc.SArray(images),
    })
    return data
```
The worst case is that the input size is 18MiB (100 * (100 * 600 * 3)), so the input is not the bottleneck. And the model is only trained once, so the graph should only be initialized once. My take is that the image training phase is a kind of memory hog.

original_comment:
The above behavior is expected due to the move -- sframes are disk backed data structures, so once loaded, they are assumed to exist on disk for the duration of when people access them.  You'd have the same issues if you moved a file being read in any other way while it was being read.

The behavior should be: 

1. Once loaded, the SFrame is assumed to be present on disk for the duration of use. 
2. When a model is saved, the relevant SFrames are present in the directory of saving (sometimes by hardlink, sometimes by writing, but it always exists in that directory).

Do you see behavior different to this?

original_comment:
The only way that you will get a scalar as output is if you only have one feature. Linear regression output is the vector x such that ||Ax - y|| has the min value. Where A is a matrix given by the dataset and the columns are the features and y is the source of true from the dataset. So you can see that x needs to have as many entries as columns of A or as features your dataset has. The only way it can be a scalar is if A has only one feature. Is this your case? Do you have a single feature? 

If you have a feature where the entry is a vector of dimension n the you can expanded into n features and do regression on those n features. For example, say you have a single feature that is given by two dimensional vectors [v1,u1], [v2,u2]...[vm,um]. original_comment:
## Overview
Multiple styles wasn't working in TuriCreate because of this silly problem.

## Issue
- The instance norm layers which determine the stylistic feature of an image are supplied by a class called the `InstanceNormDataLoader`. This data loader takes care of all of the `beta` and `gamma` weights during inference as well as the `velocity` and `momentum` buffers during training.

- Two methods exist that need to be overridden on this data loader: the `gamma` and the `beta` method.

- The instanceNorm layer in mps only supports one style meaning one `gamma` and `beta` pair.

- To circumvent this limitation, in the InstanceNormDataLoader class we created `NSArrays` to store the different `gamma` and `beta` values.

- We used an indexing variable `styleIndex` to select the different `gamma` and `beta` values for different styles.

- To export the weights after training I added a concat to the `gamma` and `beta` methods so that all of the `gamma` and `beta` weights for all styles are concatenated into one contagious block of `NSData`

- This worked during export because the part of the style transfer application TuriCreate owned was aware that these were concatenated `gamma` and `beta` values.

- this didn't work during `predict` because these concatenated values were truncated by MPS since they had no awareness that these exported `gamma` and `beta` values were for multiple styles.

- Since the gamma and beta values were contagious the truncation happened to the `gamma` and `beta` values for the first index only.

## The Solution

- Separating the methods that exported the `gamma` and `beta` weights and the methods that gave the current `gamma` and current `beta` weights for the selected style, solved this issue.

- calling `gammaWeights` and `betaWeights` gave the callee the concatenated values of `gamma` and `beta` weights for all styles

- calling `gamma` and `beta` only gave the `gamma` and `beta` values for the current selected style.

In conclusion `MPS` was happy and `TuriCreate` exported all the weights it needed for multi style style-transfer.

original_comment:
It turns out the underlying problem here is the same as the sound classifier issues: we keep reusing the default graph, which grows without bound as we add more and more operations. (Unlike the core NN models, we have to extend new graph nodes for each batch, since the precise operations being performed are randomly determined each time.)

The solution is to apply the `Graph` and `Session` types more correctly. See the introductory comments at https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/Graph and https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/compat/v1/Session
processed_comment: turn underlying problem sound classifier keep default graph without bound add unlike core extend new graph batch since precise randomly determined time solution apply graph session correctly see introductory

original_comment:
@Ridingst I think I see what's going on here. `s3fs.open()` returns a Python `File` object, which Pandas can read. Turi Create requires that the argument to `read_csv` be a string to a file on disk or on S3 (among other sources), which is incompatible with the existing `s3fs` API.

A workaround would be for your script to first get the file from `s3fs`, save it to disk, then read it with `read_csv`. This is obviously non-optimal from both a performance and code cleanliness perspective, but until `read_csv` supports reading from a Python `File` object (and the [existing S3 bug](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/issues/2278) is fixed) this may be your best bet.

I'll open (or find) an issue related to instantiating SFrames from a File object.

Thanks for bringing this to our attention.

In this way, we use this class abstraction/encapsulation to define rigorously the boundary between the old and new paths.

`mxnet==1.5.0` is only used for Python 3.7 on macOS. Note: Python 3.7 is not supported on Linux.

For Python 2.7, 3.5, and 3.6 - AVX2 support should not be needed. For those versions of Python TuriCreate uses `mxnet >= 1.1.0, < 1.2.0`. Which means `mxnet==1.1.0.post0` is used unless the user's environment has other requirements for MXNet. This version of MXNet does not need AVX2 support.

TuriCreate is currently in the process of migrating from MXNet to TensorFlow which should remove the need for AVX2 support with Python 3.7 on macOS and allow us to support Python 3.7 on Linux.

Im curious if there is any public documentation on CoreML's device selection heuristic. With the addition of 10.15's CoreML preferredMetalDevice API for MLModelConfig, I imagined it would be possible to force the MTLDevice an MLModel / Vision request runs on.

In my testing with integrated, discrete and eGPU, it appears only the eGPU consistently runs the CoreML model. My CoreML Model is a pipeline model consisting of a Mobilenet classifier with multiple outputs (multi head classifiers attached to a custom feature extractor).

Im curious to understand device selection preference for a few reasons:

a) Id like to ensure my MLModel is fed images CIImages backed by textures local to the device inference will be run on, to limit PCI transfers and keep things local

b) my model is actually fed frames of video, and WWDC '19 / 10.15 introduces VideoToolbox and AVFoundation API's to help force particular video encoders and decoders on specific GPUs.

In theory, if all works well, I should be able to specify the same MTLDevice for video decode, preprocessing, CoreML/Vision inference, and subsequent encoding - keeping all IOSurface backed pixel buffers and textures resident on the same GPU.

Apple has a Pro Apps WWDC video suggesting this is the path forward to fast path Multi GPU support / Afterburner decoder support moving forward.

Does CoreML ACTUALLY allow suggested device placement to work?

I am running a retina MacBook Pro 2018 with Vega 20 GPU, and trying various methods to get the Vega 20 to light up.

* Disabling automatic graphics switching
*  Disabling automatic graphics switching / setting NSSupportsAutomaticGraphicsSwitching to False
*  Disabling automatic graphics switching / setting NSSupportsAutomaticGraphicsSwitching to True
*  Enabling automatic graphics switching / setting NSSupportsAutomaticGraphicsSwitching to False
*  Enabling automatic graphics switching / setting NSSupportsAutomaticGraphicsSwitching to True

* having a full battery and plugged into my Apple power adaptor
* having full battery and plugged into my eGPU 

I can only on occasion get the Vega 20 to 'light up' - but can consistently have CoreML run on the eGPU (Radeon 580)

I can inspect the CoreML model and see its MLConfig has a preferred device set to the Vega 20, but Instruments, Xcode, and Activity Monitor all report no GPU usage on the Vega 20, and in fact, sometimes no GPU usage at all (not even the integrated GPU).

Any insight would be most helpful.

Apologies if this is not the best repository to post my query to.

Thanks in advance.

Hi @kid9591, this is almost certainly because of the way the iPhone captures photos and then associates EXIF data describing the phone's rotation at capture. It's likely that the photos you trained with had a different orientation than the image being used for inference.

You can view the EXIF data of a photo in Finder on macOS - this should help reveal whether the images you used were "rotated" when training the OD model.

If you have further questions please feel free to reopen this issue or create a new one.

> @shantanuchhabra now all weights are zero-inited. Do we need to make it random-inited? Will that be helpful for the training in terms of performance (I mean less iterations to converge)?

I don't think that needs to go in with this PR anyway. As far as initialization goes, here are my thoughts.

There are three checkpoints re: initialization.

1. **Have the initialization be all zeros and try to get `model.train()` to work with that.**
2.  **Add Xavier initialization with a cold start.**
3. **Add functionality to load the warm start model in C++**

1 is the current state of affairs. As far as having a working training implementation with a cold start for bitmap-based drawings goes, we can go on with this. Yes, training accuracies won't be the best but we should probably get the core feature work done before we add feature enhancements. We should add functionality for 2 and 3 at a later point, some time in the next two weeks. 

Let me know what you guys think!

Possible workaround if anyone stumbles on the same problem while I was working on a lot of images on disk.

I create random integers, sorts it, then add row numbers that you can index later. The try except clause is used to remove the column name "id" if we ran this function multiple times, since the add_row_number function does not work if you already have the same id.

```
sf_images["order_id"] = tc.SArray.random_integers(sf_images.num_rows())
sf_images = sf_images.sort(key_column_names="order_id")
try:
    sf_images = sf_images.remove_column("id")
except KeyError:
    pass
sf_images = sf_images.add_row_number(column_name="id")
```

original_comment:
The following toolkits all take a `max_iterations` parameter:
- Activity Classifier
- Image Classifier
- Drawing Classifier
- Sound Classifier
- Object Detector
- One Shot Object Detector
- Style Transfer

It seems that for following three toolkits `max_iterations` means number of mini-batches:
- Object Detector
- One Shot Object Detector
- Style Transfer

For all the other toolkits `max_iterations` means number of epochs.

I'm not sure the best way to address this inconsistency. For toolkits where `max_iterations` means mini-batches, I think it's probably fine to leave the parameter name as `max_iterations`. For the toolkits were `max_iterations` means number of epochs, we should probably change the parameter name to `max_epochs`. Regardless of naming decisions, docstrings for each toolkit should clarify if it's epochs or number of mini batches. I'm not convinced it makes sense to be able to specify *both* max epochs and max number of mini-batches for the *same* toolkit.

Hi @GaneshKumarSelvam - it looks like you are calling `tc.image_classifier.create` and passing a tuple rather than an SFrame for the `dataset` parameter (i.e. the first parameter). You need to [create a SFrame](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/sframe/sframe-intro.html) with your data then pass that to `tc.image_classifier.create`.

original_comment:
Just copying some of the MXNet details here from the other ticket 

Large Tensor Support
Before MXNet 1.5.0, MXNet supported a maximal tensor size of around 4 billion (2¬≥¬≤). This was due to uint32_t being used as the default data type for tensor size, as well as variable indexing. Now you can enable large tensor support by changing the following build flag to 1: USE_INT64_TENSOR_SIZE = 1.(Note this is set to 0 by default) This enabled large scale training for example large graph network training using Deep Graph Library.

see: apache/incubator-mxnet#9207
https://medium.com/apache-mxnet/apache-mxnet-1-5-0-release-is-now-available-4138f5233401

original_comment:
Looks like there are two issues here. One is a TuriCreate issue and one is a Poetry issue.

The first issue is that TuriCreate has transistive dependency requirements that can not be satisfied. For one reason or another this has been the case for quite awhile. We are tracking the most recent issue causing it in #2249.

The second issue is a Poetry issue. When constructing an error message for the above issue, Poetry tries to concatenate a `str` and a `int`. This can be seen by running: `poetry add -vvv turicreate` rather than just `poetry add turicreate`.

I suggest you open an issue or pull request with Poetry. Given the stack trace it should be easy to fix.

Please note: that when/if Poetry fixes their issue, you still will not be able to use TuriCreate with Poetry, because Poetry requires all dependencies to be satisfied.

Since we're already tracking the TuriCreate issue in #2249, I'm going to close this issue.

original_comment:
If you have a static confidence threshold you want to use, you could always set it at export time using the `confidence_threshold` parameter of `export_coreml`: https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/api/generated/turicreate.object_detector.ObjectDetector.export_coreml.html#turicreate.object_detector.ObjectDetector.export_coreml

Sorry for the delay in responding!

1. At present, I'm afraid the best way to guard against overfitting is to evaluate the trained model, for different numbers of iterations, against a held-out test set. We're in the process of overhauling our Object Detection implementation, and simplifying this task is something we're working on. Perhaps by just periodically giving the validation performance on a validation set, during training.
2. I cannot say with confidence how well the model will handle the occluded examples you gave, but honestly I think your three annotations are essentially what I would use. 
3. Our implementation already downloads a pretrained model (darknet) and uses that as the starting point for fine-tuning a model that regresses against your labeled data. We don't currently have a way to take, say, a detector model trained for chairs, desks, and cups and adding support for a new class while preserving the existing behavior on the old classes (without having training examples of chairs, desks, and cups to guide the tuning of the weights).

Yes, I'd think so. Looking at the other requirements there are more dependencies fixed at a specific version (`coremltools`, `prettytable`, `resampy`) which would similarly fail to install along any other library that might fix those same dependencies (or maybe allows only a narrow range).

I'm not familiar with best practices regarding dependencies for libraries, but intuitively it makes sense to bound them according to what functionality your own library actually requires, and let dependencies handle their own bounds. In this concrete case, it should be enough to restrict `numpy` in your requirements to whatever minimum version you need, and let `mxnet` handle further restrictions if they are really not compatible with a more recent version. But like I said, there might be good reasons to handle dependencies differently...

original_comment:
@MarkusShepherd - Thank you for the detailed write up. I appreciate it.

I agree we should do a better job of handling dependency versions. Relying on a range of versions would certainly be better.

Here are all of the distinct requirements for `numpy` in Python 3.6 that you shared:
```
- numpy [required: >=1.14.5, installed: 1.16.4]
- numpy [required: >=1.8.2,<1.15.0, installed: 1.16.4]
- numpy [required: Any, installed: 1.16.4]
- numpy [required: >=1.10, installed: 1.16.4]
- numpy [required: >=1.13.3, installed: 1.16.4]
```
So it sounds like we should change [our numpy requirement](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/ca6b9b02d604e03b9a8aea95b9172d3758286930/src/python/setup.py#L118) from `numpy==1.16.4` to `numpy >=1.14.5, <1.15.0`. I think this is the best we can do. What do you think?

original_comment:
# Parameters to help train Style Transfer Models

Hopefully these tips will help you achieve a better result @banoslo. It'll go over the things you could experiment with and modify to iteratively achieve the model you desire.

#### style_loss_mult

The larger the values of the `style_loss_mult`, the more stylized the image 
is. The diagram below illustrates this effect (Note: the model was trained for 
`64,000` iterations.)

![style_loss_computation](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4616962/62800465-52e44e00-ba98-11e9-8874-d8a104fa42db.png)

An example of setting the `style_loss_mult` flag is show below:

```
model = tc.style_transfer.create(styles, content, _advanced_parameters={"style_loss_mult":[1e-4, 1e-4, 1e-4, 1e-4]})
```

#### finetune_all_params

There are two different approaches to updating parameters in the style transfer 
network.

- Only update the instance normalization layers (`finetune_all_params: False`)
- Update both the convolutional and instance normalization layers. (`finetune_all_params: True`)

An example of setting the `finetune_all_params` flag is show below:

```
model = tc.style_transfer.create(styles, content, _advanced_parameters={"finetune_all_params":False})
```

##### finetune_all_params = False

**Pros**

- Trains quicker because there are less parameters to train.
- When training a model with multiple styles, the network usually converges, though the quality may suffer as a side-effect.

**Cons**

- Pre-trained weights must be used or the model doesn‚Äôt converge.
- Really limited by the convolutonal weights, the model might not be able to train past artifacts due to the low number of updatable parameters.

##### finetune_all_params = True

**Pros**

- Can converge without pre-trained weights.
- Usually leads to a model with a higher stylization quality.
- Increasing the number of iterations usually decreases the atrifacts present in the stylization.

**Cons**

- Requires a larger number of iterations to converge.
- When training a model with multiple styles, the network may never converge.

#### pretrained_weights

This option allows for the loading of pre-trained weights from a model trained 
with `32` distinct style images. For some styles, pre-trained weights can act 
as a warm-start for the training; for other styles these weights can by a 
hinderance, potentially introducting artifacts when stylizing images. As 
convergence is heavily determined by the style images chosen, further user 
experimentation is required.


When `finetune_all_params` is `False`, `pretrained_weights` is required to be 
`True` else the model won't converge.

An example of setting the `pretrained_weights` flag is show below:

```
model = tc.style_transfer.create(styles, content, _advanced_parameters={"pretrained_weights":True})
```

See [how-it-works](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/userguide/style_transfer/how-it-works.md) for the paper from which these weights were procured.

#### Checkpointing

To assist with the qualatative nature of training the style transfer network, a 
checkpointing feature is exposed in the advanced parameters section. Rather than
create multiple training loops for training models with different iterations, 
simply set the `checkpoint` flag to true and a turicreate model is saved with 
the prefix specified by `checkpoint_prefix` parameter every nth iteration which 
is specified by the `checkpoint_increment` parameter.

An example of using the checkpointing feature is show below:

```
model = tc.style_transfer.create(styles, content, _advanced_parameters={"checkpoint":True, "checkpoint_prefix":"./awesome-model", "checkpoint_increment":100})
```

If you need any additional help, let us know!

original_comment:
Let me take a pass at some of your questions!

1. The loss reported in the progress table is the "YOLO" loss defined in the model/algorithm described in our user guide here: https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/object_detection/how-it-works.html It's essentially a measure of the distance/discrepancy between what the model is currently predicting and the labeled ground truth. The smallest possible loss is 0, corresponding to predictions that exactly match the labeled data. Overfitting is certainly a potential issue. Right now, what you can do is try running the model for different numbers of iterations and comparing the resulting validation metrics on a held-out set of data. One thing we're thinking about now is how to make it easier to reason about checkpointing / early stopping to streamline this process.
2. Yes, our object detection toolkit uses transfer learning as well, in a different fashion than image classification. That toolkit relies on a fixed model to extract features from each image; the learning is done in the space of those extracted features. For object detection, we initialize a network with an existing (pre-trained) model, then tune that to fit your data.
3. I don't think you can have too much data, but yes, I think in practice it's correct to be thinking now about data quality. Ideally you want your training data to represent the use cases where the model will be deployed, so if it's going to be deployed in rooms with different floors, collecting data from different rooms could be a good idea. Manually editing the data to change out the floors should work too, if that's actually less work. (It'd be a kind of manual data augmentation.)
4. Not sure I understand your question, but in practice I would recommend just labeling the things you care about. The model should automatically learn to ignore anything you didn't label. It's perfectly reasonable to have only one class label (e.g. "person"), since you are implicitly labeling everything outside your annotated bounding boxes as "not a person".
5. Sorry, I can't offer specific recommendations or endorsements.

Hope that helps!

original_comment: The semantics of ObjC block capture are different from C++11 lambda capture (with = or &). It captures references by reference and values by value. So changing this function argument to take a `std::function` value means that the block created inside copies the `std::function`, instead of taking a reference to it.

original_comment:
@MatthewGCampbell Once you have a model in Python, you would assign it to a variable like:

```python
model = tc.classifier.create(...)
```

Then, once it's in a model variable, you can save it to disk or export it for use with CoreML. You must explicitly determine the path in both cases. If you don't call `save` or `export_coreml`, your model will not be saved to disk at all.

```python
model.save('path/to/turicreate_model') # saves in Turi Create model format
model.export_coreml('path/to/model.mlmodel') # exports in Core ML model format
```

Hope that helps!

> Yes, we can do that; it would probably be good to document it at least. ```
./configure --virtualenv="virtualenv --python=python2" --python=python3.6

original_comment:
Hey @dogahe, 

Using the item content recommender is admittedly a bit tricky.  I'm not really happy with it's overall performance and the amount of general tweaking required to get it working, and I wrote it. 

Currently, the method uses a bunch of heuristics to build a graph of what items are similar to which other items.   The distance between two items is a weight of the distances between the individual columns of the items, with the weights determined by another heuristic -- essentially the distances are weighted so that average weighted distance between all column pairs equals 1, i.e. all columns have approximately equal weight.  I'm not sure how to get these base weights, but you can supply additional weights to scale each column if you want.  Ideally, these weights should be learned, but that's not a feature we've implemented yet. 

2 is a bug.  

So, given your use case, I would recommend a bit more detailed of a process.  The same process as the item_content_recommender does under the hood (See https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/src/unity/python/turicreate/toolkits/recommender/item_content_recommender.py) can be done explicitly with the nearest neighbors toolkit, and that can be used to create a graph of item similarities by querying the model with the same data used to build it.  With that, that graph can be passed into the item_similarity_recommender using the nearest_items parameter, in which case the user -item table can just be an empty SFrame with the appropriately named columns.  This can then essentially replicate the entire item_content recommender, but give you much more control over the task.

Why is there only a basic documentation of tc?

original_comment:
> > > > > src/interfaces <- tools for interfacing to other languages, e.g. ObjC.
> > > > 
> > > > 
> > > > Not sure this one makes sense to me. Most of the directories are assumed to contain C++ code. Other language bindings like `python` and `capi` are still top level. Why wouldn't we want `src/objc` at the top level, or `src/xyz` for language `xyz`?
> > > 
> > > 
> > > This one is mostly about our code calling into objc, not calling our code from objc.
> > 
> > 
> > I see, in that case, I think this organization makes sense.

original_comment:
Hello @benjaminbraunberkeley,

Thanks for your interest in this!  I'm happy to provide you with some guidance if you want to dig into this more.  I don't think we'll be implementing this, but you're welcome to play around with it.  The sampling code is in the choose_negative_example method of src/unity/toolkits/factorization/ranking_sgd_solver_base.hpp.  

The challenge with weighted sampling strategies is that there are a lot of side effects that are not immediately intuitive here. The negative sampling works more as a regularizer on the solution than as an objective to maximize the difference between the positive and negative examples.  The real objective is to end up with a solution such that the predicted scores of the negative items -- those that the negative sampling suppresses -- are actually ranked according to the users preferences.  In other words, the question to ask is actually "Which unobserved items are most resistant to being suppressed?"  This question then leads us to assume that the sampling should be effectively exchangeable or uniform.  Thus, if you target ones that are the most "sensible" to suppress, you may decrease their predictive score while, as a side effect, you increase the predicted score of less desirable user-item pairs.  

Looking at the paper you mentioned, I'm quite skeptical.  First, it's relatively expensive to do their sampling - while theirs converges faster per iteration, each iteration is substantially more expensive than MF-BPR.    One could do 20-30 iterations of the MF-BPR method in one iteration of PRFM.  (See Figure 3 vs. Figure 4).  Second, we did not find vanilla MF-BPR to perform that well; it should be combined with choosing the negative sample as the one in a large randomly drawn pool that has the largest predicted score, then adjust the negative sampling pool size -- how many negative samples are considered before one is chosen for the sgd descent -- to accommodate users rating a small proportion of items.   This is still very efficient.   Third, AUC is a weird metric in this case for the reasons given above, and the fact that they don't give details on the number of iterations for different methods in Table 2 or Table 3 also makes me skeptical.

Sorry, my description above was not quite complete. The Vision framework gives the position of the lower-left corner (not the upper-left) because it uses a coordinate system where the origin is at the lower-left corner of the image. (This is representation used by `CGRect` in AppKit on Mac.) So y=0 is the bottom and y=480 is at the top (noting that you scaled the image to 640 x 480). So here it's more like
```
center_y_vision = 293.9184021949768 + 162.8232765197754 / 2 = 375.33
center_y_turi = 480 - 375.33 = 104.67
```
So the first line converts from the bottom of the box (in Vision coordinates, origin at bottom of image) to the center of the box, and the second line converts from Vision coordinates to Turi Create coordinates (origin at top of image).

Does that make sense?

original_comment:
Hmm, for image classification and sound classification, we only perform NN inference, so batch size only determines performance. The object detection, activity classification, and style transfer toolkits (all the toolkits with NN training that predate this year) all store the batch size, which at least in principle affects the quality of the final model by determining how many instances inform each iteration's estimate of the gradient, as well as determining how many updates are performed (when total training time is defined by number of epochs). It's quite reasonable for somebody to try training models varying only the batch size, to evaluate the effect on model quality. For that reason, I think we should store the batch size for any toolkit that updates NN weights.

Consequently, I suggest that inference-based methods default to the stored batch size by default, although certainly it's reasonable for users to override that for performance reasons. The same GPU can likely accommodate larger batch sizes for inference than for training

original_comment:
Hi @fbomb111 ,

I don't think it's possible to pip install a git repository. You could, however, clone from master, build from source, and then work with Turi Create built from source. [Here](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/BUILD.md) are the steps to make that happen.

This fix will become available in our next release, which will be in a few weeks. If you don't want to wait for the next release, here is a workaround code snippet to help you convert all the grayscale images in your SFrame to RGB so you can then visualize bounding boxes on them:

```python
import turicreate as tc
import numpy as np

def gray2rgb(image):
    # grayscale tc.Image -> RGB tc.Image
    if image.channels == 1:
        rgb_pixel_data = image.pixel_data[..., np.newaxis]
        image_rgb =  np.concatenate(3 * (rgb_pixel_data,), axis=-1)
        FORMAT_RAW = 2
        return tc.Image(_image_data=image_rgb.tobytes(),
                        _width=image_rgb.shape[1],
                        _height=image_rgb.shape[0],
                        _channels=image_rgb.shape[2],
                        _format_enum=FORMAT_RAW,
                        _image_data_size=image_rgb.size)
    return image

# Note: replace sf, "image", and "annotation"
sf["converted_image"] = sf["image"].apply(gray2rgb)

sf["bbox"] = tc.object_detector.util.draw_bounding_boxes(sf["converted_image"], sf["annotation"])
```

Feel free to follow up with more questions!

original_comment:
Materialization is kinda quirky. Here's an obviously materialized SFrame (at least obvious to me: if dryrun is for the first 100, then anything with length <= 100 is by definition materialized if you `.apply()` over it, and this is a clear case of this), for which `is_materialied() is False`):

```python
import turicreate as tc

sf = tc.SFrame({"x": [0]})  # you are not loading from a file, you should know it's of `length==1`.
sf["x"] = sf["x"].apply(lambda _: _ + 1)
assert sf.is_materialized() is False  # why not?
assert sf.materialize() is None
assert sf.is_materialized() is True
```

Why I care about this is that when I debug long pipelines with `turicreate`, I sometimes look whether an SFrame `.is_materialized()` or not. So if `.is_materialized()`'s inconsistent, it makes my debugging much harder.
