@vmalyi After reproducing the issue, we have verified that a simple augmentation fix (using a rolling window instead of a tumbling window) significantly increases the performance. Until this makes into the next release, you can use this code to work around and improve the accuracy.


```python
sessions = train['session_id'].unique()

# Now create a simple rolling window augmentation
train_augmented = train[train['session_id'] == sessions[0]]

for s in sessions[1:]:
    session_data = train[train['session_id'] == s]
    for i in range(1, prediction_window, overlapping_window_size):
        augmented_session = session_data[I:]
        augmented_session['session_id'] = augmented_session['session_id'] + 100000 * i
        train_augmented = train_augmented(augmented_session)
```

Now you can train on the augmented data and the accuracy is 30% better than the original data on this particular dataset.

It appears to be a numba bug revealed in the cfunc path of numba, which is exposed when numpy is used (as documented in numba/numba#2904. ) This bug is exposed when the a thread other than the main thread on which the python interpreter is started is actually the thread executing the function. When this happens, PyGILState_Ensure() goes down a different path and attempts to acquire a lock on the interpreter, but the main thread never releases that lock.

original_comment:
Hey @benjaminbraunberkeley, 

The models with side features have one problem which impacts training.  The reason for this is often due to thread contention on the side features -- multiple sgd updates may clobber each other with the side features, which sometimes causes these models to diverge.  Numeric side features are the worst offenders.  When we designed this algorithm, we considered putting locks around these updates, but in many cases that would have significantly slowed down the training so we did not do that.   

Also, running in single threaded mode would provide a test for this -- this can be done by starting your code with setting the environment variable OMP_NUM_THREADS="1". 

The best way we've found to avoid this scenario is to instead use a large number of categorical features instead of numerical ones.  For example, binning a single numeric feature into the 100 quantiles would help this.  Also, not having side factorization terms but lots of categories may give a good result as well. 

Negative examples are sampled from all the user / item pairs that showed no interaction.  Any user/item side features are attached to those, and the optimization is performed on those.  The sampling strategy, as well as the loss associate with them, follows this paper: https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=2484126.   Essentially, with a positive user/item data point, it samples a number of items not rated by that user, chooses the item that has the largest value, then does an SGD step on the pair attempting to increase the predicted value of the positive example and decrease the value of the negative example.  Generally we found that more samples give a more stable and better result. 

The Approx. Training Predictive Error is calculated based on the accumulated predictive error of each sample immediately before the SGD descent is provided.  This tracks the true loss quite well. 

There is no way currently to stop after an absolute loss value -- that's a good feature request, though.  You might be able to get by with adjusting the threshold of subsequent loss decrease defined for convergence -- when the loss stops decreasing above a certain rate, the model is assumed to have converged; this is adjustable.

Hope that helps!
-- Hoyt

I finally figured out what's going on here. The data in this unit test is only 106 rows. So the `random_split(.95)` used to generate the validation split will occasionally (one time out a couple hundred) generate an empty validation set. When this happens the unit test fails.

We could fix this by just making the unit test run with a greater number of rows. However I think this intermitent failure is a legitimate problem. If the `validation_set` parameter is set to `auto` and you have enough data, you should always get a validation set. It also seems wrong that if you create two different model with the exact same data, you'll likely get slightly different sized validation sets. When we do auto validation splits I think we should require an exact split.

After looking at the code I believe I've identified the issue. I'm able to reproduce this problem myself. It doesn't have anything to do with using the directory to get labels. Your code for that looks good to me.

In order for the sound classifier to use an audio clip it basically needs to be at least a second long (well 975 milliseconds to be precise). Unfortunately there is a bug in what the sound classifier does when it's asked to make a prediction for a clip which is too short. It's silently dropping it. So if you pass in an SFrame for ten wav files but one of them isn't long enough, you only get nine predictions out. This is a bug.

To answer your second question: we can currently only read wav files. So the only limitations should be that it needs to be a wav file which is at least 975 milliseconds long.

As a temporary work around, please try filtering out audio clicks that are less than 975 milliseconds. This can be done using the following code right before your train/test split:
```python
def is_at_least_min_length(audio_dict):
     num_samples = len(audio_dict['data'])
     audio_length = num_samples / float(audio_dict['sample_rate'])
     return audio_length > .975

data['is_long_enought'] = data['audio'].apply(is_at_least_min_length)
data = data.filter_by([1], 'is_long_enought')
```
Please let me know if that works.

The Sound Classifier does use transfer learning. There is no parameter for the pretained model because we currently only support one pertained model (VGGish).

In general, I would say sound classification is currently a harder problem than image classification. Also the ESC-50 dataset is not very large. Take a look at the [ESC-50 results](https://github.com/karoldvl/ESC-50#results). The highest reported results are only 86.5%. Human level accuracy is only 81.3%.

original_comment: The only_top_k is an internal property of the model and controls how many similar items are held for each item in the lookup tables.  The recommendations are an aggregation of these similar items, so often the items that are in the top k recommendations in the end are not actually in the top k for the individual items.  Thus this basically controls how approximate the model is -- the full model would use the number of items in this case, but that's both huge and overkill in practice.

There are easy, informal ways of doing this and much more rigorous ways that are harder to set up.  The quickest way is simply to use utilities like top / htop / iotop to poll the usage as you are running the program.   

At a more detailed level, there are ways of profiling memory usage in python, which will likely be helpful here (E.g. https://stackoverflow.com/questions/552744/how-do-i-profile-memory-usage-in-python).  

For disk usage, Turicreate uses a cache directory, which is given by `tc.config.get_runtime_config()['TURI_CACHE_FILE_LOCATIONS']`. Running `du` for that directory will give you idea of how much disk Turi is using. 

Hope that helps!
-- Hoyt

@elishaterada When running on macOS as the host OS, the macOS-native version of Turi Create running inside a virtualenv will definitely be the way to go. In this case, Turi Create has full access to the host OS, including frameworks like [Metal Performance Shaders](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/metalperformanceshaders?language=objc) for fast neural network routines on the GPU. If you are running inside of Docker, it will be more difficult to take full advantage of the hardware when the host OS is macOS.

If the host OS is Linux, in theory Docker should be able to take full advantage of the host OS's hardware including GPU, though this may require some extra setup and I haven't tried it.

original_comment:
@romanoss We have no immediate plans to support video data or image sequences -- could you describe your use case a bit for when we investigate those?

@adincebic We just released Turi Create 5.4, which now contains a new annotation API for image classification. Please try it out and let us know what you think! It's `turicreate.image_classifier.annotate`:

```
Annotate your images loaded in either an SFrame or SArray Format

The annotate util is a GUI assisted application used to create labels in
SArray Image data. Specifying a column, with dtype Image, in an SFrame
works as well since SFrames are composed of multiple SArrays.

When the GUI is terminated an SFrame is returned with the representative,
images and annotations.

The returned SFrame includes the newly created annotations.

Parameters
--------------
data : SArray | SFrame
    The data containing the images. If the data type is 'SArray'
    the 'image_column', and 'annotation_column' variables are used to construct
    a new 'SFrame' containing the 'SArray' data for annotation.
    If the data type is 'SFrame' the 'image_column', and 'annotation_column'
    variables are used to annotate the images.

image_column: string, optional
    If the data type is SFrame and the 'image_column' parameter is specified
    then the column name is used as the image column used in the annotation. If
    the data type is 'SFrame' and the 'image_column' variable is left empty. A
    default column value of 'image' is used in the annotation. If the data type is
    'SArray', the 'image_column' is used to construct the 'SFrame' data for
    the annotation

annotation_column : string, optional
    If the data type is SFrame and the 'annotation_column' parameter is specified
    then the column name is used as the annotation column used in the annotation. If
    the data type is 'SFrame' and the 'annotation_column' variable is left empty. A
    default column value of 'annotation' is used in the annotation. If the data type is
    'SArray', the 'annotation_column' is used to construct the 'SFrame' data for
    the annotation


Returns
-------

out : SFrame
    A new SFrame that contains the newly annotated data.

Examples
--------

>> import turicreate as tc
>> images = tc.image_analysis.load_images("path/to/images")
>> print(images)

    Columns:

        path    str
        image   Image

    Rows: 4

    Data:
    +------------------------+--------------------------+
    |          path          |          image           |
    +------------------------+--------------------------+
    | /Users/username/Doc... | Height: 1712 Width: 1952 |
    | /Users/username/Doc... | Height: 1386 Width: 1000 |
    | /Users/username/Doc... |  Height: 536 Width: 858  |
    | /Users/username/Doc... | Height: 1512 Width: 2680 |
    +------------------------+--------------------------+
    [4 rows x 2 columns]

>> images = tc.image_classifier.annotate(images)
>> print(images)

    Columns:
        path    str
        image   Image
        annotation  str

    Rows: 4

    Data:
    +------------------------+--------------------------+-------------------+
    |          path          |          image           |    annotation     |
    +------------------------+--------------------------+-------------------+
    | /Users/username/Doc... | Height: 1712 Width: 1952 |        dog        |
    | /Users/username/Doc... | Height: 1386 Width: 1000 |        dog        |
    | /Users/username/Doc... |  Height: 536 Width: 858  |        cat        |
    | /Users/username/Doc... | Height: 1512 Width: 2680 |       mouse       |
    +------------------------+--------------------------+-------------------+
    [4 rows x 3 columns]
```

Leaving this issue open for now since it was originally tracking object detection annotation -- this issue can be closed when the annotation tool also supports bounding boxes and is available under the `object_detection` namespace.

Hi @Muggle-Du ,

Here is a "hidden" API to go from a NumPy array to a Turi Create Image:
```
RAW_FORMAT = 2
tc.Image(_image_data=numpy_array.tobytes(), 
         _width=numpy_array.shape[1], 
         _height=numpy_array.shape[0], 
         _channels=numpy_array.shape[2], 
         _format_enum=RAW_FORMAT, 
         _image_data_size=numpy_array.size)
```

Note that since this is not documented in the API docs, things could change with this API and code that uses it may at some point stop working with a point release.

We are working to scope out when and how to make this API public in the meanwhile.

Hope this helps!

original_comment:
What do you mean by no-op? 
This seems to work fine.

```
#include <cstdint>
#include <iostream>
#include <ios>

template <typename T>
T bitmask(int n_bits) {
  return (T(1) << n_bits) - 1 - T(n_bits == 8 * sizeof(T));
}
int main() {
  std::cout << std::hex << bitmask<int64_t>(0) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<int64_t>(1) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<int64_t>(63) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<int64_t>(64) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<uint64_t>(0) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<uint64_t>(1) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<uint64_t>(63) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<uint64_t>(64) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<int32_t>(0) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<int32_t>(1) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<int32_t>(31) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<int32_t>(32) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<uint32_t>(0) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<uint32_t>(1) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<uint32_t>(31) << "\n"
                        << bitmask<uint32_t>(32) << "\n";
}
```

Essentially, if n_bits == bitsizeof(T), (T(1) << n_bits) - 1 == 0, so we minus 1 again to get -1.

Though technically this does depend on undefined behavior. Compiling with -fsanitize=undefined does give errors like
```
runtime error: shift exponent 64 is too large for 64-bit type 'long long'
```

Your branching version is fine. Will be great to have some tests for this.

original_comment: We'll still moving forward with a revamped Object Detector implementation (more slowly than I'd like), but I wanted to re-title this issue and narrow its focus so that your idea doesn't get lost in the shuffle. When given large images in the SFrame, we should definitely do some resizing upfront. In the general case, I suspect the main reason we don't do that already is that the data augmentation pipeline does some random cropping (within a constrained range of scales and aspect ratios), so preserving the original geometry can make a difference in theory. (For example, we take a 416x416 image and randomly crop it, we'd have to scale it back up to 416x416 for input into the network.) But given the constraints on the random cropping, etc., these should be a maximum size for the images stored.

original_comment:
> @hoytak What is a `more_thuente` routine? And what issue is this fixing?

This is the routine that sets the step size.  It requires a few passes over the data, so we do it as little as possible, but if we don't do it enough it will converge too slowly.  This fix puts in additional conditions under which to call that routine, which helps the convergence.

original_comment:
@varunlakshmanan you'll have to build turicreate to use the functionality you've coded. Even though your code is in master, you won't be able to do a `pip install turicreate` with all the updated functionality (like the feature you added) until the next release. If you build master then you'll be able to use your new functionality today.

run these commands:
1) Clone the repo if you haven't in a terminal
```git clone "https://github.com/apple/turicreate.git"```
2) Change into the turicreate directory
```cd turicreate```
3) Run configure to configure the build
```./configure```
4) Once configured change directories again into:
```cd ./debug/src/unity```
5) Then run the make command
```make -j4```
6) Change directories back into the root directory
```cd ../../..```
7) Set up your python environment with the new turicreate you just built
```source ./scripts/python_env.sh debug```
8) Now you should be able to run python and import turicreate
```python```
```import turicreate from tc```

The full set of instructions to build turicreate is located here: https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/BUILD.md

Hope that helps!
Best 
Abhishek Pratapa

Hey @KOLANICH,

> > How are you building your project?
> 
> I'm not in fact. When I saw that the prebuilt libraries zipped take 80 MiB I thought that I would wait until this issue is solved.

I'm not sure what the issue is.  Currently, our libraries are < 30MB.  The 88MB for the linux tarball comes because we have to statically link in a number of dependent libraries to get it to run reliably on linux.  If you compile it locally, you won't have this issue.  

There are ways in our build to separate out specific components if you are building the C-API, or other connectors, but it's not in our scope to do this at the python layer.  

> 
> > Are you using python here, or are you linking against the C++ components specifically?
> 
> I'm not sure that I understand right what you mean, but if you wonder, what the preferred way to build the lib for me is, it is CMake + ninja (with some customizations done using CMakeCache, I usually set `CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release` (causes -O3), add `-mtune=native`, experiment with `-march=native` and usually enable the latest c++ version to be used (this may result in better performance because of move semantics in stdlib containers and constexprs) ), and after that I call `setup.py bdist_wheel`, which should discover the lib prebuilt with CMake and create a wheel. Then I open the wheel with an archiver and add there some needed libs (I use the latest MinGW-w64 and I don't put MinGW installation dir into PATH because it would cause a conflict with Octave, using some ancient version).

In our case, we have a lot of custom build processes, and we've had an emphasis on benchmarked speed throughout.  You are welcome to play around with alternate ways of building it.  I'd encourage you to check out the BUILD.md in the base, which gives you detailed build instructions. 

> 
> If a lib uses other libs, I prefer downloading prebuilt dependencies from a trustworthy enough source (for example Fedora project distributes some libs, like Boost, prebuilt with MinGW-w64) over rebuilding them myself.
> 

In our cases, due to a combination of issues -- bugfix patches, compilation flags, etc., All our c++ dependencies are compiled from source as part of the build process. 

> > Also, is it just SFrame you're hoping to have separate, or are there other components you need separated out?
> 
> For now I'm interested in SFrame, XGBoost and LightGBM. Though I wonder, if some of this code should be moved from Turi Create into the corresponding libraries.

It's not on our roadmap to do this, though anyone is welcome to use our code. :-)

original_comment:
We should probably emit error about unsupported formats when the image is first put into the SFrame anyway, not later when the user actually attempts to use it.

Note that the issue isn't really about number of channels. AFAICT, libjpeg (which we use for all our JPEG decoding) doesn't support conversion from CMYK data to the RGB assumed by our image type. If I'm not mistaken, most JPGs are actually stored in YUV anyway, but libjpeg converts that to RGB without a problem.

(For JPEGs specifically, it is correct to check for num_channels <4, since JPEG doesn't support RGBA. We do support 4-channel, RGBA PNG files though.)

original_comment:
I understand why it is currently not supported. KNN is a method of classification that requires packing ALL (or most) of the training data into the model so inputs can be compared to the stored information. This makes it possibly the most heavy weight ML models out there, and it‚Äôs results can still be matched using Gaussian Bayesian classifiers, SVMs, and more. I would understand if Apple was not interested in exporting a model that might be larger than the destination app itself when a smaller model can be achieved using another method with just as accurate results (in most cases).

Thanks for all the help, but unless it is an intended upgrade for the future we can close this.

original_comment:
The target column is what the machine learning model is trying to predict. The feature columns are what the machine learning model uses to make the prediction. 

Taking housing data and trying to predict the sales price is a classic example of machine learning. In this example, the sale prices would the target column. The other information about the houses would be the feature columns, such as: number of bedrooms, number of bathrooms, square footage, etc.

It's possible to use those models on images, but it's probably not going to work very well. To classify images you should use our [image classifier](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/image_classifier/).

I'm going to close this issue, but let us know if you have any more questions.

original_comment:
In Turi Create 5.0, the default metrics for `object_detector` changed from `['average_precision', 'mean_average_precision']` to `['average_precision_50', 'mean_average_precision_50']`. As described in the [user guide](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/userguide/object_detection/advanced-usage.md), the version with '_50' evaluates the metric at an overlap threshold of 50%. The other metric is an average of multiple overlap thresholds.

original_comment:
@nuthinking, I'm assuming you're talking about the CoreML export for the style transfer model based on your question about `CIImages`. There may have been some confusion here. **You can actually input any shape that you want into the network!**

You're probably looking at:

https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/style_transfer/export-coreml.html

On this page you'll see: 
```swift
let modelInputSize = CGSize(width: 600, height: 600)
```

This is actually not a default size. It's a size that's defined by the user. You can change that!

**Note**: we do support a notion of `flexible_shape` in the CoreML export, so we'll be able to take any image size as an input. However, if this isn't supported on your version of MacOS (You'd get an error in XCode if it wasn't), or you'd like to explicitly set an export shape, here's how to do it:

The default CoreML export size is in-fact 256x256, as you'll see in the doc-string

```python
'''
image_shape: tuple
            A tuple (defaults to (256, 256)) will bind the CoreML model to a fixed shape.
'''
```
So in your export code, just do the following (note the `image_shape` parameter):

```python
model.export_coreml('MyStyleTransfer.mlmodel', image_shape=(2048, 2048))
```

Hope that helps, if you have any further questions I'd be more than happy to help!

One thing you could try is to create another class in your training data called "other". Put lots of randomly picked images in that class. original_comment:
Hey Yash,

Thanks for using Turi Create! I think you're running into this issue because you are trying to create an SFrame with a column called "image" that has a string (or a list of characters) as the contents. You're probably getting an SFrame with a single column called "image" that has each character of the string `'/Users/yasnara/Desktop/images_new_new'` as the elements of that column, i.e. an SFrame with a single column with a dtype of `char`. 

Note that when initializing an SFrame with a dictionary, the keys must be strings that would become column names, **the values must be SArrays corresponding to the columns with the respective column names**, and the length of all the SArrays (columns) must be the same. 

Thus, assuming the SArray with all the images is saved at `'/Users/yasnara/Desktop/images_new_new'`, you want to do the following: 

```
images_sarray_path = '/Users/yasnara/Desktop/images_new_new'
test = tc.SFrame({'image': tc.SArray(images_sarray_path)})
```

More on the SArray API documentation [here](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/api/generated/turicreate.SArray.html). 

Hope this helps! Feel free to reopen this thread if this doesn't fix your issue or if you run into any other issues!

Sweet.  I figured that out, which actually is a super-set solution to the previous problem of Python not finding mxnet when mxnet-cuxx is installed.

What's the problem?

If you uninstall any of the mxnet-cuxx versions, Python now thinks there is no mxnet installed, even if there's another mxnet-cuxx installed (or even reinstalled).

The way to fix it is to uninstall all the mxnet-cuxx versions, reinstall standard mxnet (which convinces Python that there is an mxnet, and sets up some dependencies, I bet).  Then uninstall it and install mxnet-cuxx.

That fixed it for me at least!

original_comment:
Hi @iMerica, 

Thank you for the detailed suggestions.  We'll work on incorporating them; some of these are already on our roadmap.  Currently, Turi Create runs and is tested on many production servers, clusters, and other environments, so we're happy to help remove any roadblocks in getting it working nicely in your environment. 

In reading through your post, here are a few things that may be helpful: 

First, the list of dictionary styles is supported using the unpack() function.  Lists correspond to the columns as represented by the SArray type, and SFrames are collections of columns, so to convert from the list of dictionaries, use `unpack()` to change that format to a column-based SFrame: 

```
In [3]: tc.SArray([{"a" : 1, "b" : 2}, {"a" : 3, "b" : 4}]).unpack("")
Out[3]:
Columns:
	a	int
	b	int

Rows: 2

Data:
+---+---+
| a | b |
+---+---+
| 1 | 2 |
| 3 | 4 |
+---+---+
[2 rows x 2 columns]
```
(Also, the JSON format is an arbitrary mix of lists, dictionaries, numbers, strings, etc., and if this example were given as a string, it would be valid JSON.)

Second, the recommender, classifier, and many other models do accept native types -- lists or dictionaries -- for the predict/recommend functions.  It's quite possible, though, that we've missed some.  What methods are you using that don't behave well with the native types?  

Third, for running TC in server environments, any file paths specified can be s3 (read/write) or http/https (read only) urls.  It's true that the examples assume local disk access, but they can be replaced by s3 or http paths, so `read_csv("s3://...")` should work fine.  

If you have images represented by a list of URLs, then you can call 

```
X["images"] = X["URL"].apply(tc.Image)
```

to get the data in the right format.   I filed another feature request to make this work automatically with the image classifier.  

Fourth, for the `__str__` and `__repr__` representations, what format would you find more pythonic?  The printing of native types like list, dict, or array is insanely verbose in this context, so when calling `print(X)`, we truncate it to only show the first 10 rows or so.  Note that if you have specific needs for your logging, you can simply replace these methods at runtime, e.g.:  

```
In [15]: def custom_repr(self):
    ...:     return "SFrame(" + ",".join(self.column_names()) + ")"

In [16]: tc.SFrame.__repr__ = custom_repr

In [17]: tc.SFrame({"a" : [1, 2, 3]} )
Out[17]: SFrame(a)
```

Finally, for the CoreML model export, you should be able to export the coreml path to a buffer.  I filed a new issue to make sure we do that.  In the meantime, you can work around this with: 

```
import tempfile
with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(mode='rw', suffix = '.mlmodel') as mlmodel_file:
    model.export_coreml(mlmodel_file.name)
    data = mlmodel_file.read()
``` 

Thanks!

original_comment:
Hi @thanasisDr, 

In that case, the items are selected deterministically based on the indexing of the items, which is fixed at train time; however, due to parallelism that indexing is essentially random.  In other words, the only guarantee is that subsequent calls to predict have the same ordering.  

If you want it to be random between calls, try playing with a small but non-zero value of the diversity parameter; this invokes sampling of the recommendations based on a a balance of diversity (trying to not recommend two items that are nearly identical) with recommendation accuracy, and a small value of the diversity parameter means that recommendation accuracy is pretty much all that's used there.

original_comment:
Hello @thanasisDr,

After all the similarities have been computed, a sparse item-to-item lookup table is built that holds, for each item, a list of the most similar items as determined by overlapping content.  All the items are considered, but only the top max_item_neighborhood_size are actually saved and used for prediction.  However, all are considered when building the model.

Note also that by default, the item content recommender doesn't include user access patterns in its recommendations, only the content provided with the items.  To add in user interaction patterns, add a column containing a sparse dictionary of the users interacting with each item as an item feature.   (There are several ways to get the data in for this; e.g. use groupby + concat if you have a table of user-item interactions).

original_comment:
Hi @dogahe, the reason the model in CoreML only supports interactions and not users for querying is that we typically don't want each user to get access to the interaction history of all users. If the model were to allow for querying by user ID, since it's the same model for all users, any user could in theory query for any other user's recommendations without knowing their interaction history (or even open up the model file and examine other users' interaction history directly, if they have access to it). As the model developer in Turi Create, this doesn't expose any information it shouldn't (since you are starting with the data comprised of interaction history for all users anyway), but for privacy reasons we don't expect that such a database should be given to all the users of your app.

Presumably the use case for an on-device recommender model is to get recommendations for the current user (not necessarily any other user). And our assumption is that for the current user, it should be possible to programmatically retrieve their historical interactions. Could that assumption allow you to query for the recommendations for the current user? (Note: this also means the current user didn't necessarily need to be in the training data, whereas if you query by user ID they would need to be.)

To give an example, suppose the user ID is `1234`, and their interactions within the app are rating items `x`, `y`, and `z`, each with rating 5 (note: use `-1` as a placeholder if the model was trained without explicit ratings). So to get the same result as calling `recommend(users=[1234])` in Python, you'd call something like `[model predictionWithInteractions:@[@"x": 5, @"y": 5, @"z": 5] k:5]` in Objective C using the CoreML model. This is the equivalent of the [`recommend_from_interactions`](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/api/generated/turicreate.recommender.item_similarity_recommender.ItemSimilarityRecommender.recommend_from_interactions.html#turicreate.recommender.item_similarity_recommender.ItemSimilarityRecommender.recommend_from_interactions) method in Python.

Please let us know if this works for your use case, or if not, why not. For now I'll leave this issue open as a doc bug, since we should update the [user guide chapter](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/recommender/coreml-deployment.html) to make it clear how to consume the Core ML model.

original_comment:
On a complete side note - when you do end up doing this for the AC as well - note that the AC doesn't actually need 4 dimension shapes. One of the dimension (Height by my convention) is always `1`.  
If no other toolkits are using the `LowLevelApi` (none should) - you can probably skip these conversions altogether, and stick with a single 3-dim shape. 

As you might recall - the MXnet implementation has some [redundant transposes and reshapes](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/src/unity/python/turicreate/toolkits/activity_classifier/_mx_model_architecture.py#L25), which further complicate the weights layout.  
These operations can be removed Using MXnet>0.12 APIs, and then it should be quite easy to find a simple, common layout for both MXnet and MPS.

original_comment:
As I've been experimenting quite a bit with getting the performance in order -- I've been able to get Turi Create to utilize much, much more of my GPUs power; not all of it, but a much more sizeable chunk.

To do this -- I resized the data images that were originally taken with my iPhone X and iPhone XS. Previously, I had only compressed them but did not resize them. Once I compressed them gently and resized them to 416x416 (without maintaining the aspect ratio) using preview in MacOS, I had file sizes of less than 200kb each. Once I trained the images in Turi, things trained much more quickly and for the first time ever, I was able to see my 5 GPUs use roughly 100w of power each, with their utilization on each sitting between 60% and 100%. I increased my batch size to about 560, which pushed my 5 GPUs (GTX 1080Tis) to their limit without receiving memory errors.

I figured that if the issue was with a bottleneck in the Python script's performance (even with my 18-core CPU (due to lack of script optimization) that if I resized them ahead of training that I'd have less of a bottleneck. That seems to be the case. 

Most importantly, the model's performance is spectacular when used in my app in a real-world setting -- the resizing of source material to 416x416 without maintaining the aspect ratio and my gentle compression (using jpegoptim) didn't seem to hurt things as far as I can tell. My evaluation in Turi and in real-world usage accurately detects models with a 88%+ confidence score.

I used RectLabel to annotate my data and was concerned that I would have to spend many many hours redoing previous work after resizing the images; but after opening up the resized images in RectLabel, the bounding boxes adjusted appropriately without having to redo that part of my work. I'm not entirely sure how that worked out in my favor, but I'm happy it did!

original_comment:
Thanks Prash for the question. Here is the specific implementation we use in the current style transfer toolkit: https://arxiv.org/pdf/1607.08022.pdf

## Networks

There are two different networks used.

- A generator network we call Transformer. `src/unity/python/turicreate/toolkits/style_transfer/_model.py:106`

- A VGG-16 network that's used for training the Transformer Network. `src/unity/python/turicreate/toolkits/style_transfer/_model.py:192`

## Training

The training process is as such.

### Forward Pass
- A forward pass through the Transformer Network using the Content Images.
- A forward pass through the VGG-16 Network using both the Content and Style Images respectively

### Style Loss
- We keep track of the outputs after some of the activation layers `[relu1_2, relu2_2, relu3_3, relu4_3]` we calculate the gram matrix using the outputs of these activation layers for the Content and Style Images respectively. `src/unity/python/turicreate/toolkits/style_transfer/style_transfer.py:316`

- The addition of these losses is the `style_loss`

### Content Loss
- An additional L2 loss is computed between the output `[relu3_3]` after the forward pass of the Content and Style Images we call this the `content_loss`

### Total Loss
- We add the losses together and only update the beta and gamma weights in the InstanceNorm layers of the Transformer Network.

Repeating this training process in a training loop allows us to create a Transformer network that can quickly stylize images. See `src/unity/python/turicreate/toolkits/style_transfer/style_transfer.py:283` for the training loop.

I hope this explained the process in which we train the style transfer model.

This could be done by using the [coremltools package](https://github.com/apple/coremltools) to add meta data to your mlmodel. 

Something like the following should work:
```python
import coremltools

turicreate_model.export_coreml('my_model.mlmodel')
core_ml_model = coremltools.models.MLModel('my_model.mlmodel')
core_ml_model.user_defined_metadata['class name'] = type(turicreate_model)
core_ml_model.save('my_model.mlmodel')
```

In your iOS app, you can then use the [metadata property](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/coreml/mlmodeldescription/2879386-metadata?language=objc) of the [MLModelDescription](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/coreml/mlmodeldescription?language=objc) class to get the value for `class name`.

original_comment:
Ah, I'm glad you elaborated on what you are trying to do. So, what that refers to is that you should not be inconsistent in what you annotate as samples. However, if you say for instance that you don't want partially occluded objects to be detected at all, that is a consistent behavior that the model can learn. With that said, you have many choices of what to do with occluded objects.

1. Ignore the occlusion and define the bounding box as if the object was fully visible.

2. Take the occlusion into account when defining the tight bounding box (this is popular in the academic literature).

3. Choose not detect partially visible objects at all.

All these three are consistent behaviors that the model can learn. The choice is entirely up to what you want the detector's behavior to be.

> And to clarify my "train twice" question, what I'm asking is if there's a way to use my existing model for transfer learning expand it's capabilities. It seems now that I have to start from scratch each time. Is that correct?

Yes, this is correct. We do not have support for this currently.

original_comment:
Hi @sejersbol, sorry for the really long delay here!

Unfortunately I do not know where the breaking point is, and of course it will depend on acceptable evaluation metrics and training data size.

From a technical point of view there is no hard limit and if you go to extremes there could be Core ML model size issues and memory issues during inferences. However, that will only happen for extremely large number of classes.

From a modeling perspective (which is a problem that will happen much earlier than the technical limitation) it is not as clear. As you increase the number of classes, you increase the risk of making classification mistakes. Although, the severity of a lot of the mistakes should simultaneously go down as you will have more and more classes that are naturally similar (breeds of dogs, etc.). The original YOLO9000 paper (https://arxiv.org/pdf/1612.08242.pdf) trained a model using 9000+ classes with reasonable results (lots of mistakes of course, but still impressive). They trained it on a combination of detection and classification data, so if they actually had detection data for all 9000, then results would presumably be even better.

In your experiment it sounds like 50-60 was OK (thanks for giving us a sample point!). Anything below 100 is definitely tried and true, as long as you have the data. However, will 300 do OK? Will 1000 do OK? Theoretically I would say yes, if you are able to provide enough training data and you adjust your expectation of what a good evaluation metric is, since you know you'll make more mistakes. For instance, for classification with 1000 classes, it is common to report top-5 accuracy (that is, the correct label is in your top-5 classes for a sample).

Hi @henrytkirk. Really sorry for the long delay!

Any unrecognized field added to the annotation dictionary will be ignored by the model. Let me present some alternatives, but I will first make some guesses as to what you are trying to achieve. My guess is that you have for instance N classes and for certain objects you want to mark if the instance is occluded or not. Now, we do not have support for multi-label detection, which would mean having separately independent targets (1. class, 2. occlusion yes/no).

However, you can pre-combine these two targets, so that your new "classes" are:
* class1
* class1-occluded
* class2
* class2-occluded
* ...

This is not quite ideal, but it may work out.

As for your second question of training the model twice. I assume you mean starting the training from an already trained model, right? No, this is currently not supported. It's related to checkpointing (#574), although that feature request does not explicitly specify if it should be possible to resume training. This is something that we have discussed, but we have not committed to supporting it at this point. It introduces a lot of reproducibility issues and it is also not trivial how to set learning rates fully automatically in such a setting.

original_comment:
Hi @eddydas, thanks for the feedback!

As a matter of fact - the Activity Classifier is a general purpose time series classification toolkit. It is agnostic to which sensors you select for your task, as long as you use the same sensors for training as the ones you will use for real time prediction.  
It is definitely not limited to motion sensors (thought that is of course the classical use case) - any sensor measured at a constant rate may be used - e.g. heart rate, depth sensor, luminance sensors etc.    
Even in the case of motion sensors - the choice of inputs is up to the library's user, and changes from one project to another. While some applications may benefit from using `motion.gravity.x + motion.userAcceleration.x` as you've suggested, others may want to use `motion.userAcceleration.x` alone to detect certain movements of the phone itself.

The purpose of the [documentation page](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/activity_classifier/export_coreml.html#applying-the-core-ml-model-in-an-app) was simply to show how to use an activity classifier trained model in an iOS app, regardless of the specific use case.

Having said that - since the example used throughout the documentation section, HAPT dataset, **does** use total acceleration (including gravity) - you're probably right üòÑ . The documentation should at least be consistent.  
I'm leaving this issue open, and I agree with @znation's P3 label.

original_comment:
CreateML uses a different base model by default. You can use the same base model as Create ML using the following:

```
model = turicreate.image_classifier.create(data, 
                      target='is_expensive', model = 'VisionFeaturePrint_Screen')
```

More details here:

original_comment:
It depends on the data. Honestly, I suspect that this is fine for most datasets most of the time. If the window only has two unique labels, then the algorithm is correct. So it's only wrong if the window has three or more labels, and none are in the majority.

For example, the HAPT dataset in the user's guide has a prediction window of one second's worth of samples. Then the algorithm _could_ do the wrong thing if the window contains an interval of less than half a second labeled with A, preceded and followed by two distinct labels B and C. You would think that for most domains, you would choose a prediction window whose granularity matches the data labeling granularity to some degree.

But while I think this may not be a critical bug to fix (AFAICT, we've had it for a while), it should not be hard to implement a fix. The histogram may even be faster than Boyer-Moore, since it involves fewer branch instructions.

original_comment:
We should definitely do step 1 of what Ilai suggested. Step 2 is really a separate matter, since this case is less about the validation_set='auto' and more about allowing users to invoke our validation-set creation code to produce test sets. #969 covers a separate case: the fact that we currently throw an exception if the test set doesn't happen to span all of the labels present in the training data.

With regard to step 2, note that most of our supervised toolkits currently just use the heuristic of using a validation set when the number of instances is above 100. I think the main question here is what is an "instance". A session feels like it's much bigger than an instance, since it may comprise several prediction windows, each of which has a separate (if not independent label). Given that our implementation already splits each session into segments of 20 prediction windows, we could in theory do the auto split if we have at least 100 of these 20-window segments. But that's nontrivial to compute accurately, and is probably best implemented on the C++ side as part of the chunking code. (Chunk first, then split.)

original_comment:
Its not a bug. We can impute multiple features. Here are some scenarios. All of these share the same API at the moment and they all impute.

- Single row prediction on a dataset with multiple features and one is missing
- Single row prediction on a dataset with multiple features and two are missing
- Single row prediction on a dataset with one feature and that one is missing
- Batch prediction on a dataset with a single feature in a single row missing
- Batch prediction on a dataset with a many rows containing a single feature missing
- Batch prediction on a dataset with a many rows containing a single feature missing and some containing two features missing
- Batch prediction on a dataset with an entire feature missing

The principle applied during imputing is a point estimate that minimizes the variance in the prediction. Its not a bug at all and is completely by design to accommodate a consistent API and behavior for all of the cases above.

original_comment:
Hi @tetreault,

Actually - it's the other way around üòÑ   
We've added a safeguard in v.50b3 that prevents from creating an automatic validation test if the dataset is too small. The reason, as I have mentioned above, is to try to prevent the case that both train and test sets contain only part of the labels (motions).   
I admit this decision is done rather crudely - we simply don't allow splitting if there's less than a certain amount of sessions (currently hard coded to 100).  

In addition - the safeguard was added mainly to prevent the `activity_classifier.create()` function from creating an auto validation set. In no way it should block a user who is explicitly calling the `random_split_by_session()` API. 

I'm changing this issue to a feature request, so we will add:
1. As a first step - an enforce flag to `random_split_by_session()`, allowing the user to split his sessions on any dataset when using this API.
2. We should probably improve the decision mechanism for whether or not to create a validation set during `create()`. It should check the labels distribution of the train and validation sets (or some other method) - rather then a hard limit on the number of sessions.

@nickjong - mind if I assign this FR to you? Feel free to re-assign it to whoever relevant.

In iOS, (x, y, width, height) x, y is the origin, but here in your library it is the center of the box, I was confused. Everything works perfectly now! ```python def row_to_bbox_coordinates(row): """ Takes a row and returns a dictionary representing bounding box coordinates: (center_x, center_y, width, height) e.g. {'x': 100, 'y': 120, 'width': 80, 'height': 120} """ return {'x': row['xMin'] + (row['xMax'] - row['xMin'])/2, 'width': (row['xMax'] - row['xMin']), 'y': row['yMin'] + (row['yMax'] - row['yMin'])/2, 'height': (row['yMax'] - row['yMin'])} ``` Here is the code that I have written so far. I am not a python programmer, so please reserve judgement. What I wanted to do is, take what I had in the csv file, and combine it with the data that I get when I open the images directory. ```python import turicreate as tc import os csv_path = 'out.csv' csv_sf = tc.SFrame.read_csv(csv_path) def row_to_bbox_coordinates(row): """ Takes a row and returns a dictionary representing bounding box coordinates: e.g. {'x': 100, 'y': 120, 'width': 80, 'height': 120} """ return {'x': row['xMin'], 'width': (row['xMax'] - row['xMin']), 'y': row['yMin'], 'height': (row['yMax'] - row['yMin'])} csv_sf['coordinates'] = csv_sf.apply(row_to_bbox_coordinates) # delete no longer needed columns del csv_sf['id'], csv_sf['xMin'], csv_sf['xMax'], csv_sf['yMin'], csv_sf['yMax'] # rename columns csv_sf = csv_sf.rename({'name': 'label'}) csv_sf = csv_sf.rename({'image': 'name'}) # Change if applicable images_directory = 'Acne-and-Rosacea-Photos' # Load all images in random order sf_images = tc.image_analysis.load_images(images_directory, recursive=True, random_order=True) # Split path to get filename info = sf_images['path'].apply(lambda path: os.path.basename(path).split('/')[:1]) # Rename columns to 'name' info = info.unpack().rename({'X.0': 'name'}) # Add to our main SFrame sf_images = sf_images.add_columns(info) # Original path no longer needed del sf_images['path'] # Combine label and coordinates into a bounding box dictionary csv_sf = csv_sf.pack_columns(['label', 'coordinates'], new_column_name='bbox', dtype=dict) # Combine bounding boxes of the same 'name' into lists sf_annotations = csv_sf.groupby('name', {'annotations': tc.aggregate.CONCAT('bbox')}) # Join annotations with the images. Note, some images do not have annotations, # but we still want to keep them in the dataset. This is why it is important to # a LEFT join. sf = sf_images.join(sf_annotations, on='name', how='left') # The LEFT join fills missing matches with None, so we replace these with empty # lists instead using fillna. sf['annotations'] = sf['annotations'].fillna([]) # Save SFrame sf.save('images.sframe') # Load the data and preview the data data = tc.SFrame('images.sframe') data['image_with_ground_truth'] = \ tc.object_detector.util.draw_bounding_boxes(data['image'], data['annotations']) data.explore() ``` ```csv image,id,name,xMin,xMax,yMin,yMax acne-excoriated-8.jpg,1,excorciated,194,271,80,144 acne-excoriated-8.jpg,2,excorciated,337,406,320,384 acne-excoriated-8.jpg,3,excorciated,545,626,295,377 acne-pustular-20.jpg,1,pustular,100,147,235,280 acne-pustular-20.jpg,2,pustular,225,260,120,146 acne-pustular-20.jpg,3,pustular,243,282,169,199 acne-pustular-20.jpg,4,pustular,344,368,262,288 acne-pustular-20.jpg,5,pustular,345,369,294,316 acne-pustular-20.jpg,6,pustular,261,289,304,342 acne-pustular-20.jpg,7,pustular,214,246,305,334 acne-pustular-20.jpg,8,pustular,164,203,271,306 acne-pustular-20.jpg,9,pustular,160,177,229,247 acne-pustular-20.jpg,10,pustular,190,276,237,269 acne-pustular-18.jpg,1,pustular,364,379,123,137 acne-pustular-18.jpg,2,pustular,108,124,22,38 acne-pustular-18.jpg,3,pustular,89,100,168,192 acne-pustular-18.jpg,4,pustular,153,180,215,233 acne-pustular-18.jpg,5,pustular,316,338,345,363 acne-pustular-18.jpg,6,pustular,542,582,279,312 acne-pustular-18.jpg,7,pustular,477,506,261,284 acne-pustular-18.jpg,8,pustular,579,596,322,346 acne-pustular-18.jpg,9,pustular,545,569,145,161 acne-pustular-18.jpg,10,pustular,76,97,48,66 acne-pustular-18.jpg,11,pustular,367,389,272,289 acne-pustular-18.jpg,12,pustular,219,233,262,276 ... ```

Copy of my previous reply in the other thread:

First - please verify that you use the latest `turicreate` version, 5.0b3. There was a bug recently fixed in `random_split_by_session()`. You can do it by either running `pip freeze | grep turicreate` in shell, or `print tc.__version__` in python.

In addition, can you please provide the output of the following prints?
```
len(dataSFrame['exp_id'].unique())
len(train['motion'].unique())
len(test['motion'].unique())
```
It seems that your train set only contains two sessions? Is that correct?  
The train set should contain examples from all supported activities. During training a mapping is created that maps all supported activities to integers, and this mapping is used by the prediction/evaluation functions. It is also advisable that the test set contain a mixture of all activities (though not mandatory).

I'm surprised you even got a valid train-test split. The `random_split_by_session()` function is not intended for very small datasets - from the very reason that it is not likely to randomly include all activities if the data is too small. It should have errored out and refuse to do the split below a certain number of sessions (currently hard coded to 100).

original_comment:
This issue is much more subtle than it appears. I'm not exactly sure this is the right fix and I don't think we should take this fix for 5.0. Its an issue that requires quite a bit of discussion.

We chose to make predictions using the most information we have during prediction time. The default option for prediction is imputing when features are not present during predict time.  For a single example, if a single feature is missing, imputing is probably the right thing to do. In batch mode, if one example in one row is missing, imputing a single value is the right thing to do. When you add these two things up and want a consistent API, the current API is the only choice. 

The user always has the option of turning off imputation in all the predict calls but that's not the default option. Changing the default will revert the "right" thing to do in those other cases but make this case less of a surprise. We could warn the user that we are imputing a lot of data and still continue.

I have not verified any tests for the Intel graphics MPS code path, since this code path is not currently supported.

Image classification has two phases: feature extraction using a neural network and logistic regression based on the extracted features. The logistic regression currently always runs on CPU. The feature extraction is the same for both training and inference, and always uses CoreML, which should use GPU or CPU, as available.

Activity classification training and inference both use either MPS (on Macs with AMD GPUs) or MXNet (using GPU or CPU, as available).

original_comment:
We have updated several issues with this previously, but usually these issues boil down to numerical inaccuracies that are next to impossible to prevent.  The main reason is that the boosted trees model often uses values from the training dataset in determining the split points.  At these specific values, calling the models at these specific values can often give a different prediction.  

The reasons for this are usually due to two things. First, the training is done with float32, but predictions in CoreML are done with float64, and minor differences in the numerical values cause the model to go down different branches, and these different branches will have different predictions.  Second, converting from decimal values to float32 or float64 (e.g. reading from a CSV file, giving it explicitly, etc.) will produce slightly different numbers.  In other words, each of the following routes can be a different number:  decimal->float64, decimal->float32, decimal->float64->float32, float64->float32, etc.  As a result, if the original value was present in the training data, each of these paths may give a different prediction.  Thus, when testing boosted tree model export, it's very difficult to use values from the training data.

original_comment:
@AndrGolubkov There is currently no special support for this. What you can do is simply add more classes with the appropriate sub-components. For instance, you can place an additional box over the fingertip and make that a separate class. However, the algorithm will not be aware of the hierarchical relationship, so it won't tell you that a hand instance is a parent of a particular fingertip instance. You would have to add this kind of reasoning yourself based on the raw predictions (possibly looking at how close they are spatially, if they have consistent size, etc.).

I hope that gives you an idea of how it can be done at least!

original_comment:
@johnyquest7 Are you sure then that CUDA is installed? Since it can't find `nvcc`, it means at least your PATH is not pointing to the CUDA location.

If CoLab installs it in a different path, perhaps it also sets an environment variable describing where it is. Check:

```
env | grep CUDA
```
You can also try something like this to see if if the CUDA include directory is being picked up:
```
echo '#include <cuda.h>' | cpp -H -o /dev/null 2>&1 | head -n1
```
If neither of those work, it looks from our end that CUDA is not installed. As a sanity check you should also check if you can run the command `nvidia-smi`. However, this command comes with your NVIDIA drivers and not with CUDA, but it will be a pre-requisite for installing CUDA, so that command should be available at least.

original_comment:
@cianiandreadev @amiraeitan Including the post-processing actually does two things, the first the obvious and the second less obvious:
1. It removes duplicate predictions over a single object, an artifact of the underlying algorithm. See [this image](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/object_detection/export-coreml.html#non-maximum-suppression) for an example. The output format is the same with `include_non_maximum_suppression`, but the suppression of such duplicates is built in.
2. It also makes the output recognizable by the Vision framework. If we don't have the post-processing included, the Vision framework will not recognize the output as bounding box output. In this case, we have to interpret the output manually, which is described in the user guide that I linked to.

So, I wouldn't expect to get a `VNRecognizedObjectObservation` if the post-processing is not included in the mlmodel. We'll work on reproducing this and see what we can do on our end to handle these failure cases better!

original_comment: Sure.  It's covered at a high level in the user guide.   Basically there are two goals with a recommender system -- the first is to provide an accurate prediction of the score (i.e. the error is RMSE), and the other is to recommend items that, with high confidence, have a high score but with which you don't really care about the actual predicted score.  There are a number of cases where using just a prediction of the score is bad -- e.g. an item has a single perfect rating, and the solution is to use a different objective that focuses on predicting only items that have a high score. These tend to perform much worse on RMSE errors but much better on Precision-Recall tasks.

Thanks for the prompt response yesterday to my inquiry - great to know how active the team is, gives me more confidence in using it.

is there any information you can share (or pointer to the SFrame/GL github, for the flow that was used in the _internal.search functionality, which I could replicate externally to the modules, for example leveraging some of the text_analytics components to create my own functions that leverage the functionality in turicreate to obtain similar results?

Now, let me share a bit about how i'm using it.

I have been using the SFrame module to analyze, cluster and group a couple of public data sets. Two in particular.
1) all retirement plans in the US since 2009. The SFrame modules have been extremely useful. The data is openly available from https://www.dol.gov/agencies/ebsa/about-ebsa/our-activities/public-disclosure/foia/form-5500-datasets
2) all 990 IRS tax filings for Exempt Organizations https://docs.opendata.aws/irs-990/readme.html

Both of these datasets are based on human entered data, which can both vary from year to year, and in some cases are intentionally differentiated. Particular search fields are company names. Various attempts to normalize the company names led to more complexity and edge cases. Eventually I loaded the data into elasticsearch which allowed me to search the data, but not so useful for pythonic analysis. Inverted index searching was the way to go.

Eventually I stumbled upon the _internal.search model function and started to use it for pythonic data analysis - taking a name, looking for similar ones using the search criteria, and adding those to a new column in the SFrame, so i could then use that to normalize the data (using EIN's as the key). Amongst other uses, such as creating a dashboard that lets a user search for a company/plan name across multiple fields (Company name and Plan name in the retirement dataset can reinforce and rank higher something that otherwise would not) Additionally there are nested objects inside of another column that has service provider data, and i do an index on that information to search for plans that for example have "fidelity" as a service provider to the retirement plan. It does a great job providing me a with a quick queryable list of candidates, without loading all the data into solr or es to generate the queries, and keeps everything inside of python, i can also generate models for subsets, and deploy the model to AWS lambda (my intention) to support much quicker, analysis for multiple iterations that are needed on some functions. (i could also use ES for this going forward, which is my current approach in lieu of the search model).

One hypothetical example is "BLUE CROSS BLUE SHIELD" while they are all different entities (regional and local), they all belong to a collective group. This is noted either in their plan name, mailing address, administrative name, etc.) and in different formats, spellings, abbreviations, etc. These are across both 401k and 403b plans. 

I create multiple search models (k) is for 401k plans and (b) is for 403b plans

```
m_srch_sfmain_k = gl._internal.search.create(sfmain_k, features=['SPONSOR_DFE_NAME', 'PLAN_NAME', 'SPONS_DFE_CARE_OF_NAME','SPONS_DFE_DBA_NAME'], verbose=False)
m_srch_sfmain_k.save('m_srch_sfmain_k')
m_srch_sfmain_b = gl._internal.search.create(sfmain_b, features=['SPONSOR_DFE_NAME', 'PLAN_NAME', 'SPONS_DFE_CARE_OF_NAME','SPONS_DFE_DBA_NAME'], verbose=False)
m_srch_sfmain_b.save('m_srch_sfmain_b')
```


For each of the search models, i then look for the highest likelihood candidates, parse the dates, extract the service providers, and generate a matrix based on those that have a score of N.

```
bcbs_k = m_srch_sfmain_k.query("BLUE CROSS BLUE SHIELD",
                               num_results=1000)['score',
                                                 'ACK_ID',
                                                 'FORM_TAX_PRD',

                                                 'TOT_CORRECTIVE_DISTRIB_AMT']
bcbs = bcbs_k[bcbs_k['score']>20]
bcbs['year'] = bcbs['FORM_TAX_PRD'].apply(lambda x: dateparser.parse(x).year)
bcbs_ackids = list(bcbs['ACK_ID'])
sfc2 = _sfc2.filter_by(bcbs_ackids,'ACK_ID')
sfc3 = _sfc3.filter_by(bcbs_ackids,'ACK_ID')
bcbs['location'] = bcbs['SPONS_DFE_MAIL_US_ZIP'].apply(lambda x: get_location(x))
bcbs['recordkeeper'] = bcbs['ACK_ID'].apply(lambda x: get_rk(x,sfc2,sfc3))
bcbs['invest_adv'] = bcbs['ACK_ID'].apply(lambda x: get_invadv(x,sfc2,sfc3))
bcbs['brokerage'] = bcbs['ACK_ID'].apply(lambda x: get_brokerage(x,sfc2,sfc3))

original_comment:
Hi @vmalyi,

Please see attached a [notebook](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/files/2199413/auto_workout_classifier_turi-create.ipynb.zip) with my analyses.  

I'm afraid that my main conclusion is that I couldn't find any set-up in which the AC performs significantly better on this dataset.  
The main reason, I believe, are the short sessions. Having short sessions of 10 sec each, with a prediction window of 2 seconds - means that every session only has about 5 windows on it.  
Since the RNN in the AC is learning across these windows - having such short sequences (5 samples long) makes it hard for the RNN to gain much knowledge.

I'm leaving this issue open, and changing it to a feature request.  
We would definitely take this use case in consideration, in future development of the Activity Classifier. There is no reason why datasets like yours shouldn't be supported.

Hi @baizhenmao95, in the code examples there, `img` refers to a single [Image](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/api/generated/turicreate.Image.html), whereas it appears in your code, `img` refers to an [SArray](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/api/generated/turicreate.SArray.html) containing images. To operate on each one, you could pull them out individually, like:

```python
from PIL import Image
# note the [0] - this extracts just the first image from the SArray
Image.fromarray(img[0].pixel_data).save('test.jpg')
```

Or, you could run a lambda function over the SFrame to save all images in parallel. For this, you would need another SArray containing the desired filename (let's assume it's called "filename"):

```python
from PIL import Image
# make a temporary SFrame to associate images with filenames
temp_sf = tc.SFrame()
temp_sf["img"] = img
temp_sf["filename"] = filename
temp_sf.apply(lambda row: Image.fromarray(row["img"].pixel_data).save(row["filename"]))
```

original_comment:
Hi @vmalyi, 

Thank you for trying out the Activity Classifier, and for the elaborate feedback!

As you can imagine - the session id is indeed stripped in the pre-processing stage. Before training the DNN - the sessions are being cropped into non-overlapping, constant length time sequences.  These constant length sequences (let's denote them "chunks") are the actual training samples being fed to the network.

The main motivation behind the session id requirement is to make sure that samples from two separate users don't get into the same chunk (instead - the last chunk of each sessions is being padded and then weighted out by the loss function).  
Another advantage of using sessions is it provides a single identification for consecutive data from a specific user. If we would have used time stamps only - data taken at the same time from two different users might have gotten intermixed. Or alternatively by using user_id only - two different recordings, taken at completely different times, might have been fused together to the same chunk.  
Lastly - using sessions improves the train-test split mechanism. Splitting whole sessions increases the test set's independence, by making sure that correlated chunks coming from the same user don't end up in both the training and the test set. 

Can you please share some more information about your human activity recognition problem, and the algorithms you've been comparing with?  
The AC have been tested with several similar datasets (multi-class human activities, such as running, walking etc.). We have tried to design the AC to generalize well for a wide variety of datasets.  
Any additional information would be of course welcome - as we try to improve AC performance even further.

original_comment:
@yousifKashef Yes, Turi Create allows multiple bounding boxes per image. See the [user guide chapter](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/object_detection/#data-acquisition) for object detection. The format for bounding boxes is a JSON object for a single bounding box, or a JSON array of multiple JSON objects for multiple bounding boxes.

There is no reason to limit to one bounding box per image; you can have as many bounding boxes as the number of objects in the image. I would recommend including a bounding box for all objects in the image, that are of a class that is labeled with one of the labels you are trying to predict.

original_comment:
Okay, we've figured out that this problem is ultimately due to running out of memory on the GPU. A smaller batch size resolves the issue. We should make the batch size scale automatically according to available memory, but in the meantime you should be able to get things going by changing your invocation to something like:
```
model = tc.object_detector.create(train_data, feature='image', annotations='annotations',
    _advanced_parameters={'batch_size' : 16})
```
Note that if you specify the number of iterations explicitly, you'll need to double that number to achieve the same number of passes through the training data. (The current default batch size is 32.)

original_comment:
Hi @yousifKashef,

To read this kind of JSON format into SFrame, it would be easiest to use the built-in `json` package, since that type of structure (a single object with key/value pairs) doesn't map directly to the SFrame table structure and thus isn't supported by `turicreate.SFrame.read_json`. Instead, we can provide that mapping through code:

```python
import json
import turicreate as tc

# read the JSON file into an in-memory object
with open('file.json', 'rb') as f:
    obj = json.load(f)

# get that JSON object into SFrame format (gives a single column of [key, value])
# note that `items` is what allows us to map this key/value structure into a table structure
sf = tc.SFrame(obj.items())

# transform the SFrame into two columns, and rename them appropriately
sf = sf.unpack('X1')
sf = sf.rename({'X1.0': 'path', 'X1.1': 'annotations'})
```

original_comment:
Hi @vpndemand, if I understand your question correctly, you want to use a different folder for each label (with the name of the folder representing the label) as the data for an image classifier. For this task, I would do something like this. Make a folder structure like this, for separating the images by label:

```
‚ûú  ~ find images
images
images/cat
images/cat/cat1.jpg
images/cat/cat2.jpg
images/dog
images/dog/dog2.jpg
images/dog/dog1.jpg
```

Then, in Turi Create, you can load these images and manipulate the `path` column to get the label:

```python
import turicreate as tc
sf = tc.image_analysis.load_images('images')
"""
sf is:
+-------------------------------+--------------------------+
|              path             |          image           |
+-------------------------------+--------------------------+
| /Users/zach/images/cat/cat... | Height: 1199 Width: 1200 |
| /Users/zach/images/cat/cat... |  Height: 400 Width: 600  |
| /Users/zach/images/dog/dog... |  Height: 486 Width: 729  |
| /Users/zach/images/dog/dog... |  Height: 455 Width: 680  |
+-------------------------------+--------------------------+
"""
sf['label'] = sf['path'].apply(lambda x: x[len('/Users/zach/images/'):])
"""
sf is:
+-------------------------------+--------------------------+--------------+
|              path             |          image           |    label     |
+-------------------------------+--------------------------+--------------+
| /Users/zach/images/cat/cat... | Height: 1199 Width: 1200 | cat/cat1.jpg |
| /Users/zach/images/cat/cat... |  Height: 400 Width: 600  | cat/cat2.jpg |
| /Users/zach/images/dog/dog... |  Height: 486 Width: 729  | dog/dog1.jpg |
| /Users/zach/images/dog/dog... |  Height: 455 Width: 680  | dog/dog2.jpg |
+-------------------------------+--------------------------+--------------+
"""
sf['label'] = sf['label'].apply(lambda x: x[:x.find('/')])
"""
sf is:
+-------------------------------+--------------------------+-------+
|              path             |          image           | label |
+-------------------------------+--------------------------+-------+
| /Users/zach/images/cat/cat... | Height: 1199 Width: 1200 |  cat  |
| /Users/zach/images/cat/cat... |  Height: 400 Width: 600  |  cat  |
| /Users/zach/images/dog/dog... |  Height: 486 Width: 729  |  dog  |
| /Users/zach/images/dog/dog... |  Height: 455 Width: 680  |  dog  |
+-------------------------------+--------------------------+-------+
"""
```

Then, you can proceed to train using the `label` column as the label. Hope this helps! Please reactivate this issue if your question is not answered, or open a new issue if you have a different question, thanks!

original_comment:
Hi @iAmNaz,

As a matter of fact - I've just finished fixing this bug, the fix is coming up in a few hours üòÄ.

As for a workaround - there are two simple options:
1. When you're calling  `create()`  - pass in the param `validation_set=None`. This will train the model without a validation set.
2. Use your own validation set. If you've already saved aside a few of the training sessions - just pass them in as another SFrame, to the `validation_set` param.
For example:
```
train = tc.SFrame(sessions_1-200.csv)
valid = tc.Sframe(sessions_201-250.csv)
model = tc.activity_classifier.create(train, ... , validation_set=valid)
```
Make sure to pass in whole sessions (don't split the same session between test and valid) and have even distribution of the target labels (e.g. "walking", "running" etc) in both training and validation sets.

original_comment:
Hi @bobdillon48, please see the [User guide chapter](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/object_detection/#data-acquisition) on Object Detection, which gives examples of the JSON format used for describing the bounding boxes. The bounding box description for a single row (where each image's metadata is a row of your CSV), would look something like this:

```json
[{"coordinates": {"height": 104, "width": 110, "x": 115, "y": 216}, "label": "ball"}]
```

Note that there could be more than one object annotation per image, which is why this is a JSON array. I think a single object is also valid.

To construct a CSV file that would describe each image this way, you'd want two columns, one for the path to the image (relative paths from within a directory where you will execute the script tends to work best), and one for the annotations. The resulting CSV file would look something like:


```csv
path,annotations
images/image1.jpg,[{"coordinates": {"height": 104, "width": 110, "x": 115, "y": 216}, "label": "ball"}]
images/image2.jpg,[{"coordinates": {"height": 208, "width": 40, "x": 48, "y": 29}, "label": "tree"}]
```

Then, you can read the resulting file into SFrame format with `turicreate.SFrame.read_csv` and join it to your images with `join` (assuming the path column name is the same, and contains the same image paths, in both SFrames).

I'm also going to leave this issue open and tag as `docs`, so we can use it to track updating the documentation to make it clearer. Now that I'm reading that user guide section, it's not clear how to get these JSON annotations into a CSV file (i.e. what's the right CSV syntax), how to load that into SFrame format, and how to combine it with the images SFrame.

Turi Create links directly with libpng and libjpeg, and we recently changed `pixel_data` to rely on this instead of PIL. In the spirit of avoiding unnecessary PIL dependence, I think we should use our own direct linkage here as well.

original_comment:
Sounds like the biggest issue here is that the side effects are inconsistent: the first n rows can have side effects (because the lambda runs in-process for type inference) but subsequent rows cannot (because the lambda runs out of process). Two possible fixes to make this a better UX:

* Run the type inference pass in a separate process, just like the real lambda workers -- this way the behavior will be consistent across all rows/dataset sizes.
* Add an API parameter to force in-process execution (slow, but perhaps intentional for side effects). Could be "allow_side_effects=False" by default or something.

This is strange. It looks like Core Video adds nullability only if the environment supports it. This is determined in `CoreVideo.framework/Versions/A/Headers/CVBase.h`:

```

For some reason, this `#if` must be evaluating to false on @avlaskin's environment, while still complaining that nullability is missing (so the environment obviously supports nullability).

original_comment:
The hi-res images could be causing memory issues. During training, the model is fed images resized down to 256x256, so there will be no benefit of providing content or style images larger than this. You can still stylize images of any size.

So, one thing you could try is to scale the images down. You can do that for instance doing:

```python
images = tc.load_images('images/')
images['image'] = images['image'].apply(lambda img: tc.image_analysis.resize(img, 256, 256, 3))
images.save('resized.sframe')
```
Now, you can load that SFrame directly in your training script. This is actually what we do at the onset of training, but I'm worried that we are still keeping the hi-res images around in memory.

Also, the warnings that you mentioned are not important. The `h5py` seems unrelated to Turi Create, since we do not depend on that package. When loading images, it will warn every time it sees a file that was not PNG or JPEG, but this is safe to ignore. We shouldn't be warning about hidden files like `.DS_Store` at all though, so I filed an issue for this in #641 (thanks for pointing this out!).

original_comment:
@mdenty  Thanks for trying it out! Sorry, you are not seeing GPU utilization.

Is this your iMac: https://support.apple.com/kb/sp688?locale=en_US ?

If so, the reason why you are not seeing GPU acceleration is because the graphics card is NVIDIA and  not AMD (as in more recent Macs). Not to worry though, since we also have support for NVIDIA graphics cards.

There are a few more steps to set this up however. First, make sure you have CUDA installed, for instance CUDA 8. Optionally install cuDNN as well, which will lead to greater performance. Finally, uninstall MXNet (`pip uninstall mxnet`) and install the CUDA-enabled MXnet (corresponding to your CUDA version):
```
pip install mxnet-cu80==1.1.0
```
More information can be found here:

https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/LinuxGPU.md

These instructions assume that you are on Linux, since that's the OS of most of our CUDA users. Right now we do not have any instructions for how to set up CUDA on Mac (and I'm being  vague in my instructions simply because I have not gone through these steps myself). We should add this, so any feedback or tips you have in setting this up, we'd love to hear. Thanks!
