original_comment:
Hi @frogg 

I'm glad to hear that you're finding Turi Create helpful for building your AI powered app!  
Have your tried the [activity classification toolkit](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/activity_classifier/)? It's designed specifically for this kind of tasks.

Let me try to answer all of your questions:
> Is Turi Create optimized for Apple Watch classification?

TC is degined to support any kind of ML task, on a variety of OSes and devices.  
Having said that - the ability to easily create Core ML models makes it a perfect tool for creating powerful Apple Watch, iOS and macOS applications.  
Activity classifcation using Apple Watch and iPhone sensors was of course tested and demonstrated to be an exelnet use case for TC.
> Is it important on which body part the device is located? In the demos I've only seen iPhone-like devices in the pocket.
What if I recorded training data on the left wrist and someone wears their watch on the right wrist?

As in any machine learning model, training on a wide range of scenarios would asisst the model to generalize and get better results.  
It hard to tell how a model would behave before actually testing it - but of course that introducing a completely different scenario on inference, which the model never had the chance to train on, is likely to produce poorer results.
> Which parameters of CMDeviceMotion would be best to feed into Turi Create? Right now I use `.userAcceleration` and `.rotationRate`?

We generally don't tend to advise on project specific details.  
On a general note - some classification tasks would benefit from using calbrated readings, such as `.userAcceleration` and `.rotationRate`, while others would produce better results by using raw sensors readings such as `.CMGyroData`.  
My best advice would be to try both approaches (no point in intermixing them, as they're corelated with each other), and see what works best for your use case.

Feel free to approach with any more questions and clarifications!

original_comment:
@jsrpy - `tc.recommender.util.compare_models` is not intended to plot anything. Take a look at the [API doc for that function](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/api/generated/turicreate.recommender.util.compare_models.html).

With the code you gave `compare` will be a list of length two. The first element of the list will correspond to your first model (i.e. `model_0`) and the second element will be for your other model (i.e. `model_1`) . Both of the elements of `compare` contain the precision and recall (both overall and by user) at various cutoffs.

So for example, if you are interested in overall precision for `model_0`, you can access that using:
`compare[0]['precision_recall_overall']`. This will show you both the precision and recall for all cutoff values.

Hope this helps. Let us know if you have more questions.

If you're interested in all the statistics available in `SFrame.show()` (and more!) - the `SArrray.summary()` returns an object with many interesting stats per that SArray.
You can aggregate over all of your columns, to get a list of these objects, by doing:
```
[sf[c].summary() for c in sf.column_names()]
```

original_comment:
Hi @VlamV 
If you're interested in getting a specific static, such as mean, std, max etc - here are two possible workarounds:
```
[sf[c].summary().mean() for c in sf.column_names()]
```
will give you a list of mean values, and
```
sf.groupby([], [tc.aggregate.AVG(c) for c in sf.column_names()])
```
will return a new SFrame, with the mean value of each column.

Do note that some of the stats returned by `SArray.summary()` (such as quintiles) are approximations, while others are exact measurements. You can see more details [in the API documentation](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/api/generated/turicreate.Sketch.html#turicreate.Sketch).

original_comment:
Hi @andremontenegrof, the correct way is the second (empty list), although None may also work.

Let's look at your example of adding an empty list to an SArray. So, this SArray will be a list where each element represents an image. If I re-write what you had as one element per line, it looks like this:
```
train_data2_annotations = [
  {'coordinates': {'y': 32, 'x': 147, 'width': 290, 'height': 67}, 'label': 'Sneaker'}, 
  {'coordinates': {'y': 1124, 'x': 1777, 'width': 105, 'height': 265}, 'label': 'Sneaker2'}, 
  [],
]
```
Every element must itself be a list. So, if you intended for this SArray to hold the information for three images, the last one being a pure negative, it should have the following format:
```
train_data2_annotations = [
  [{'coordinates': {'y': 32, 'x': 147, 'width': 290, 'height': 67}, 'label': 'Sneaker'}], 
  [{'coordinates': {'y': 1124, 'x': 1777, 'width': 105, 'height': 265}, 'label': 'Sneaker2'}], 
  [],
]
```
I hope that clears things up!

original_comment:
Hi,

I recommend lowering the maximum cache capacity to maybe about 2GB. i.e. 
```
tc.config.set_runtime_config('TURI_FILEIO_MAXIMUM_CACHE_CAPACITY', 2*1024*1024*1024)
```

Also, you don't need 5000 iterations in 
```
tc.image_classifier.create(train_data, target='label', max_iterations=5000)
```

original_comment:
Hi @johnyquest7, I thought I would add some more detailed info. All vision toolkits (classifier/similarity/detector) perform implicit resizing to get the data into a fixed size expected by the underlying model. For instance, the ResNet-50 backend for the classifier takes a 224x224 image, so if you provide an image of size 500x400, it will be automatically resized to 224x224 before passed to the model. It may violate the aspect ratio doing this, but the classifier networks are pretty robust to this kind of deformation. There is no cropping involved.

This is what happens at test time for all three models and during training for classifier/similarity. The object detector during training on the other hand does extensive data augmentation, which means each time an image is presented to the algorithm (each image repeated many times) will be randomly resized, cropped, translated, color perturbed, and mirror flipped.

original_comment:
Hi @LennartOlsen,  sorry that you're having this problem

A few things that come to mind:
1. Are you initializing your `dataArray` at some point? It should be initialized (probably to zeros) before the first calls to `predict()` - so if any of the sensors' readings are missing, you would still have some numerical value in the array.
2. It seems that you're only casting Accelerometer data to `Float`. Are the other sensors guaranteed to be floats? Can you try casting these as well?
2. Better yet - can you please try casting all of them to `Double`? (it seems that your `Measurement` is defined as `Double` anyway). The exported model probably expects `Double`s as input (you can check by double-clicking the `mlmodel` file in Xcode).
3. Could it be that you sometimes call `PerformPrediction()` with only part of the sensors in `dataEntry`? For example with a Gyroscope measurement only, but without new Magnetometer reading? 
If so - the other sensors must be attended to somehow (filled with some default values). 
Otherwise - you keep calling some of the sensors with their previous readings, and in case of the first call - with some uninitialized values.  

Could you please try running a simpler model with just one of the sensors, just to rule out all of the possible errors above?  
Could you also please try using your code (all 3 sensors), on the same devices, but with the built-in sensors?  

Last but not least - if none of the above helps, could you please try to record some data from your sensor and send it in some format (csv etc)? I'd like to try to reproduce your problem, using your app, in order to debug it.

original_comment:
Hi @johnyquest7 , thanks for your question

Theoretically, TC's visualization tool should allow you to plot the ROC by using the `tc.show()` function:
```
turicreate.show(ev['roc_curve']['fpr'], ev['roc_curve']['tpr'])
```  
However, as mentioned in https://github.com/apple/turicreate/issues/142, it's not yet possible to request a specific plot type (a scatter plot in this case) - so sadly the plot won't show correctly for the moment.  

The quickest workaround is to use `matplotlib`:
```
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.scatter(ev['roc_curve']['fpr'], ev['roc_curve']['tpr'])
```
If you're using Jupyter notebooks, you can add `%matplotlib inline` after importing `matplotlib`, this will make the drawing appear within the notebook.

original_comment:
Hello @ubuntudroid,

Sorry for the delay in answering your question -- missed it when you first asked it.

The recommender models (or all of our models, currently) stay the same once created.  You'll have to retrain the models on the old and new data combined to get an improved model.  However, they do accept additional observation data with the recommend function, as you pointed out, and this is used to improve the recommendations at that specific call to recommend.  It's pretty much the same as having it be part of the original data in the first place in terms of accuracy, but it is slower.

The workflow use of the recommender model that we were envisioning is to have the models be retrained and validated regularly, but to have data accumulated since the last training be passed in to `recommend()` to keep the context and recommendations current.

original_comment:
@Padalingam -

1 - ResNet is used to get what are called deep features. You can think of it as basically a dimensionality reduction from the input, where the input is the RGB values for each pixel. A logistic regression is then trained on these deep features. 
For details, see: https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/userguide/image_classifier/how-it-works.md
The actual code is [here](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/ca62331a2161332a2e49fca1d6926325cc71519b/src/unity/python/turicreate/toolkits/image_classifier/image_classifier.py#L115).

2 - Yes, I think so. Recognizing different parts of a chair certainly seems like an Image classification task.

3 - I think you are going to need more data (i.e. images to train on). I've had success training on only 30 examples per category but that was for categories that are visually distinct from each other. Given how similar different parts of a chair look, I think you're going to need much more than 30 pictures per category.

original_comment:
Hi @Padalingam, thanks for trying out the image classifier! Before the classifier is used, it downloads a model file from the internet and it looks like Turi Create wanted to put the model in a location that you don't have access to. This should not happen and is a bug that we need to address. Thanks for bringing it to our attention!

In the meantime, I think I have a work-around for you. The directory where the model gets saved can be manually specified using the environment variable `TURI_CACHE_FILE_LOCATIONS`. I see that you are on a Mac, so this typically involves adding the following line to the end of `~/.bash_profile` (if you don't have this file, then create an empty one first):

```
export TURI_CACHE_FILE_LOCATIONS=~/turicreate
```

Of course, you can choose the location yourself, but I recommend placing it in your home directory under `~/...` to ensure permissions to write to it.

Please restart your terminal after making the change.

original_comment:
@johnlev We have traced down the bug to the presence of a byte-ordered mark in your file. This is corrupting the read_csv of SFrame resulting in columns that contain non-ascii characters

```
sf.column_names()
['\xef\xbb\xbfb1', 'b2', 'b3', 'b4', 'b5', 'room']
```

The simplest work around is for you to remove the marker from the file which you can do with a simple sed script. 
```
awk 'NR==1{sub(/^\xef\xbb\xbf/,"")}1' all2.txt > all2_byte_ordered.txt
```

We will be fixing the underlying issue in  #227. Hopefully that should unblock you to use Turi Create in your application.

original_comment:
The calculated loss is actually meant to be the "mean loss per sequence" and not "mean loss across timestamps‚Äù although in my experience they are quite similar for activity classification.

In order to calculate the mean loss across timestamps, notice how `loss_per_seq` is weighted, so the correct calculation would be: `loss = _mx.sym.sum(loss_per_seq * seq_sum_weights) / (_mx.sym.sum(seq_sum_weights) + 1e-5)`

The same applies for the accuracy calculation.

original_comment:
In practice I've found that YOLO9000's accuracy isn't as good as SSD or Faster R-CNN (speed is another story, YOLO is very speedy). YOLO can also be more challenging to train, depending on the task. As you also noted, YOLO doesn't work well with small objects. Of course, this is based on my own experiences.

It's impossible to say "this architecture is always the best" because (as we know) which architecture + training procedure is best is _highly_ dependent on the dataset, task, and project.

My general rule of thumb is that if speed isn't a concern, Faster R-CNN is a good starting point. If speed is paramount and accuracy can suffer a bit, give YOLO a try. If a middle ground is needed, start with SSD variants (SSD + MobileNet for speed; SSD + Inception for potentially higher accuracy but longer inference time) and go from there.

Again, that is just my rule of thumb from my own personal experience training these networks on a number of datasets. Whether or not it holds up to a particular task is highly dependent on the data and overall goals.

original_comment:
The current behavior is exactly what you mentioned; everything is implicitly castable to string.  And I agree with you -- I think it should be either strict or follow the semantics of to<...>(), not somewhere in between. 

The weird behavior in question is due to the following use case.  The Levenstein distance is exposed directly through the extensions mechanism as 

`double levenshtein(const std::string& a, std::string& b);`

The test that's failing simply calls this function with a list and a dict types and asserts that an exception is raised -- i.e. the previous behavior here raised an error; the new mechanism does not.  

I suspect that what changed is the converter did actually change behavior in this, but the implicit casting behavior went through the flex_list converter method and showed up only here.  Thus the old converter didn't match the behavior of the class and now it does.

original_comment:
@igiloh I think I misspoke with IDEs - this change is intended for editors that don't do their own build, and don't have proper completion without the aid of external plugins. Those plugins typically depend on something like `compile_commands.json`.

I tested it with the [YouCompleteMe](http://valloric.github.io/YouCompleteMe/#c-family-semantic-completion) vim plugin and it works -- I get true semantic completion instead of the normal vim "tag"-based completion.

A few other tools that I haven't tried, but claim to be compatible with this `compile_commands.json` file:

* [linter-gcc](https://atom.io/packages/linter-gcc) for Atom
* [vscode-cpptools](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode-cpptools/blob/master/Documentation/Getting%20started.md#how-to-specify-the-include-paths) for Visual Studio Code
* [flycheck-cmake](https://github.com/xwl/flycheck-cmake) for Emacs
* [auto-complete-clang](https://github.com/xwl/auto-complete-clang) for Emacs

I also measured the perf of the build on each branch, over 5 runs each, with the command:
```bash
rm -rf debug/ release/ && ./configure && pushd debug/src/unity && time make -j8 && popd
```

In my 5 runs, there was no difference between the wall clock time of the build on `master` and this PR branch. (In fact, this branch was 2s faster on average, but with a stdev of around 5s.) See [compile_commands perf impact.txt](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/files/1633054/compile_commands.perf.impact.txt).

Okay, the test failure is really a question about correct behavior.  Suppose we do this: 

flexible_type f = 1.0; 
flex_string s = f;  // Error or cast? 

With this PR, this goes through the "to<flex_string>()" operator, which does not error out in this case.  

Previous behavior was a mix of to<...> and get<...> depending on the types.  

Should this implicitly cause a cast?  

If we go with "no" universally, it's not backwards compatible -- double and int are cast to each other. 
if we defer to the to<...> operator, then it's more liberal than current. 

I'm inclined to have it be strict with get<...>, except for numerics.

@Olamyy Good question, and I'm tagging this issue as `enhancement` to track supporting separately and selectively turning off or re-routing debug/info/warning/error messages printed from turicreate.

I think the ideal state here is:

* No output is directly sent to `stdout`, with the exception of APIs like `print_rows` that explicitly print to the console. Such APIs should have non-print equivalents (like `rows`) that simply return the value as a string.
* No output is directly sent to `stderr`.
* Debug/info/warning/error messages are routed through the Python [logging](https://docs.python.org/2/library/logging.html) API, with a consistent and predictable module naming scheme (perhaps all of `turicreate`, or perhaps sub-modules), so the user can control from Python which strings are sent where.

original_comment:
Thanks @znation, that is really useful overview! I think we need to distinguish model save/load and SFrame save/load though, at least from an implementation point of view. Right now, SFrame in Python 3 automatically decodes strings as UTF-8 (likewise in Python 2 when displaying strings). This does not happen automatically for the model states for some reason, which is exactly what this PR does manually. If the model states behaved like SFrames, this PR would not be needed at all.

As for the SFrame, its behavior is essentially Option 1 right now. This mostly works except for two main issues (and a separate bug that I just opened an issue for in #157):
- In Python 2 only bytes indexing is supported and in Python 3 only unicode indexing is supported
- Python 2 and 3 both support saving byte strings that are not valid UTF-8. In Python 2 this is mostly fine (printing fails with a missing symbol), while in Python 3 this is a fatal error.

That we are allowing non-ascii/non-utf8 bytes to go into an SFrame is not great, since these should probably more appropriately use the `array` type in the first place. There is an option between 1 and 2 where we keep the Python 2 behavior but introduce deprecation warnings (that we could wait to enforce strictly until a major version bump). Apart from the breaking change, the fact that Python 2 and 3 only support indexing with their respective `str` is a bit strict, but it is consistent with Python 3 behavior in general:

```python
>>> {b'foo': 100}[u'foo']
```
This works in Python 2, and it doesn't matter what combination of  `b` and `u` you have. The same exact discussion applies to regular values and string equality checks (`b'foo' == u'foo'`). However, if your key is a unicode with non-ascii characters, then you can't index it with a byte string (even if it's utf-8 encoded). In Python 3, indexing across bytes and unicode is simply forbidden altogether even if you only have ascii in your strings. What makes Turi Create's behavior a bit weird is that whatever you put into the SFrame, you always end up with UTF-8-encoded bytes in Python 2, and unicode in Python 3. This can lead to unintuitive indexing or equality checks where the value you just put in does not seem to match what you get out:

Currently in Python 2:
```python
>>> key = u'\u00aa'
>>> tc.SArray([{key: 100}])[0][key]
KeyError
>>> tc.SArray([{key: 100}])[0][key.encode('utf-8')]
100
>>> tc.SArray([key])[0] == key
__main__:1: UnicodeWarning: Unicode equal comparison failed to convert both arguments to Unicode - interpreting them as being unequal
False
>>> tc.SArray([key])[0] == key.encode('utf-8')
True
```
Currently in Python 3:
```python
>>> key = b'foo'
>>> tc.SArray([{key: 100}])[0][key]
KeyError
>>> tc.SArray([{key: 100}])[0][key.decode('utf-8')]
100
>>> tc.SArray([key])[0] == key
False
>>> tc.SArray([key])[0] == key.decode('utf-8')
True
```
I purposely made this example using an SArray, since that means the `KeyError` or the equality check is happening from a native Python data type and not directly from an SFrame/SArray. Of course, for things like SFrame column indexing, we could theoretically support dual bytes/unicode indexing and do the encode/decode implicitly. However, we could not extend this kind of support to the example above or two equality checks. That is, under Option 1 or 2. If we introduce a separate string type, as Option 4 proposes, then we could avoid this type of inconsistent behavior.

I'm not sure Option 4 as you describe it is even possible. The reason is because we already support unicode input in Python 2 and it has the implicit UTF-8 encoding behavior as outlined above. So, if we keep Python 2 behavior exactly (assuming compatibility with 4.0), the new text type would only ever be used in Python 3 when a unicode object is used. This would be really strange in many ways, especially since Python 2 would then be able to open and load these as unicode, but if the information is re-saved it would again go in as a UTF-8-encoded bytes. It would also be strange to have two unicode-supporting string types.

For Option 4 to really make sense it would have to be more like Python 3, where the Turi Create bytes/unicode would share semantics with Python's bytes/unicode types (and UTF-8 is never implied. although it can be an implementation detail for the unicode type). However, that would be a pretty major breaking change to the current behavior. Probably much more disruptive than the breaking change in Option 2.

I don't think Option 3 offers an acceptable UX in Python 3.

original_comment:
@jrosebr1 thanks again for the extremely detailed report!!!

SFrames are lazily evaluated, so SFrame operations which you're performing aren't actually being calculated until the data is required. The `sf.materialize()` method forces that SFrame to perform all of the operations in its calculation graph.
`materialize` is usually useful if you've performed several pre-processing steps, and are about to iterate over the same SFrame (as in the case of several training epochs etc.).
However, materializing is irrelevant in your case, since SFrames built by `SFrameBuilder` will always be materialized.

Nevertheless - using `SFrameBuilder` might explain the HD explosion, as the SframeBuilder uses a very large cache, as described in https://github.com/apple/turicreate/issues/102.

While I'm downloading the entire dataset and trying to reproduce the problem - I'll be really glad if you could please upload a small subset of about 10-15 images, with their respective CSVs (after you conversion from xml). I wanna try to load the data a bit differently, without looping over the CSVs and adding images one by one.

original_comment:
@gustavla Hmm. I think we have lots of options here to resolve this issue (correct me if any of these won't work):

1. Assume strings contain `utf-8` encoded text when necessary to make an assumption for Python 3, and error out otherwise. Python 2 would still continue to work with arbitrary byte strings, but the models and data produced may not be loadable in Python 3. (I think that's what's in this PR?)
    * Pros: non-intrusive code change, no UX change to existing scenarios.
    * Cons: Turi Create in Python 3 would not quite be compatible with Python 2 in terms of behavior/data/models.

2. Require strings to contain `utf-8` encoded text, and validate this in both Python 2 and Python 3 to prevent incompatibilities between the two. Note: this would potentially break loading existing SFrames or models from 4.0.
    * Pros: full compatibility between Python 2 and Python 3.
    * Cons: breaking compatibility with 4.0, no support for arbitrary byte strings or other encodings.

3. Keep the same semantics in Python 3 as in Python 2, which implies we would only ever use the `bytes` type in both. (Currently, we use the `str` type in both, but this has different semantics in Python 2 and Python 3; as I understand `bytes` has the same semantics in both Python 2 and 3 as our current semantics, and is what `str` maps to in Python 2).
    * Pros: full compatibility between Python 2 and Python 3, full compatibility with 4.0.
    * Cons: not very Pythonic (in Python 3 especially). Users expect the `str`/`unicode` type to work in Python 3 (and probably the `unicode` type in 2 as well).

4. Add a new `text` type in SFrame that implies utf-8 encoding and uses the `unicode` Python type; this is basically option 2 + option 3. We could potentially rename the current `str` type to `bytes` as well to remove confusion.
    * Pros: full compatibility between Python 2 and 3, full compatibility with 4.0.
    * Cons: two string types. This could cause user confusion (in the same way that Python having two string types does üòÑ ). However, I think the biggest source of confusion is the word `str` and could be resolved by just calling the types `bytes` and `unicode`/`text`/etc.

original_comment:
Hi @radikal9,

To see a summary of the entire SFrame (aggregated view for each one of the SFrame's columns) - please use the `sf.show()` method. Note that only the 50 first columns are presented.
To drill down to a larger view of a specific column, please use `sa.show()` - for example by calling `sf['my_column'].show()`.
If you're interested in browsing the table itself, use the `sf.explore()` method - which opens an interactive view of the entire data.
Finally, to see 2D plots (x, y) such as scatter, heatmaps etc - please use `tc.show(x ,y)`.
You can see more examples and instructions in the [visualization section of the user guide](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/vis/introduction.html).

Feel free to suggest further visualization features.

original_comment:
Hi @johnyquest7, thanks for trying out the detector! An empty list is a valid return if the model did not find an object with enough confidence. However, if you are getting this on an image where you feel there is an object that it should find, then we need to figure out why it wasn't able to learn this.

First of all, try lowering the confidence threshold. This should give you a lot of bounding boxes (although many of them seemingly random with very low confidence):

```python
model.predict(sf, confidence_threshold=0)
```

Is the top prediction at least somewhat reasonable? If not, then I would go back to your training data and visualize it to make sure everything looks good. You can also try making a prediction on a training sample - the model should get this right with high confidence. Also, how many classes and samples did you have in your training set? Let me know and hopefully we can track down the issue. This kind of feedback is really helpful for us, so thanks a lot!

original_comment:
@mattzheng In the meantime, you could use NetworkX or another package to draw relatively small graphs, for example:

```python
import networkx as nx
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from turicreate import SGraph, Vertex, Edge

# construct an SGraph (skip this if you already have one)
sg = SGraph()
sg = sg.add_vertices([Vertex(i) for i in range(10)])
sg = sg.add_edges([Edge(i, i+1) for i in range(9)])

# convert to NetworkX graph
g = nx.Graph()
g.add_nodes_from(sg.vertices['__id'])
g.add_edges_from(sg.edges.apply(lambda row: [v for (k,v) in row.items()]))

# Draw it and show on screen
nx.draw(g)
plt.show()
```

original_comment:
At first, I thought this was a bug but now on second thought, I think this is correct behavior. There are 2 concepts:

1. All group-by operators in turicreate follow the skip None policy i.e they will omit all missing values from the aggregation.  As an example, `sum([None, 5, 10]) = 15` if you assume that the None is skipped. 
2. Additionally, in python/pandas/numpy etc, `sum([]) = 0` which is exactly what turicreate does as well. 

Hence, using the skip None policy and the sum of nothing is 0 policy, we get an answer of zero when you are trying to do `sum([None]) = sum([]) = 0` for the group `a`.

With the same principle in mind, we cannot get 0.0 for the mean because the mean is undefined if there are no points. Hence, using the skip None policy, we have `mean([None]) = mean([]) = None (undefined)` and hence you get None.

We can make the case that None values are skipped more clear in the groupby documentation. I'll file a separate issue for that.

original_comment:
Thanks for trying out the object detector! I really appreciate the detailed report of this bug, since it made it very easy for me to understand the issue. The problem is that we are not handling images with 4 channels (RGB + opacity channel) correctly.

I will work on a fix and in the meantime let's discuss work-arounds to get your model working. If you want to train the model to leverage the opacity channel, then the current version will unfortunately not support that. However, if you get rid of the opacity channel then this error message will disappear. You can either manually convert your images before loading them, or you can do it through Turi Create:

```python
def drop_alpha(image):
    return tc.Image(_image_data=image.pixel_data[..., :3].tobytes(),
                    _width=image.width,
                    _height=image.height,
                    _channels=3,
                    _format_enum=2,
                    _image_data_size=image.width * image.height * 3)

sf['image_rgb'] = sf['image'].apply(drop_alpha)
```

Removing the opacity channel of an image can be done in several ways. The question is, do we replace the transparent background with white or black, or something else? The above method is blunt and simply drops the opacity channel. This will work if most of your images do not actually use the extra channel. However, if they do use it, it may lead to visual artifacts so I encourage you to check the new images manually with `explore()`. Let me know how it works out!

original_comment:
This is what I ended up having to do to get it to work as I mentioned in my previous post.




```python
class WriteWorker(Thread):
    def __init__(self, savePath):
        Thread.__init__(self)
        self.images = []
        self.annotations = []
        self.queue = Queue()
        self.daemon = True
        self.savePath = savePath
        self.start()

    def run(self):
        while True:
            r = self.queue.get()
            self.images.append(r['image'])
            self.annotations.append(r['annotations'])
            self.queue.task_done()

    def wait(self):
        self.queue.join()
        sf = tc.SFrame({'image':self.images, 'annotations':self.annotations})
        sf.save(self.savePath)
```

You are right, the SFrame `from_sql` function currently does not work with SQLAlchemy. [Pandas documentation](https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/version/0.21/generated/pandas.read_sql_query.html) suggests that they support:

* sqlite3 DBAPI2
* SQLAlchemy connectable(engine/connection)
* database string URI

The SFrame [from_sql](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/6225cd5e31f743d10b9cd3b5f4c6d1cca683d161/src/unity/python/turicreate/data_structures/sframe.py#L1611) function only supports DBAPI2. It would be awesome if you could look into SQLAlchemy. This wasn't on our immediate radar.

*  [SFrame Builder class](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/api/generated/turicreate.SFrameBuilder.html)

original_comment:
Thanks for describing your pain points in great detail! We know that setting up the data for the object detector is tricky and appreciate all the feedback we can get to help make the process easier.

It looks like you are all set, except for one thing. Each cell in the `annotations` column must contain a list of dictionaries. This is to allow more than one object per image. Of course, if you are only planning to have one object per image, that is perfectly fine too and I have trained successful detectors on such data. However, we still need it to be a list in that case. You can correct this for your data by calling:

```python
data['annotations'] = data['annotations'].apply(lambda x: [x])
```

This will put what you have now into lists of length 1 and the detector functions should be happy.

I would just like to clarify that my intention here is not to diminish this project or the talent of its contributors.

For a slightly broader context, companies like Apple, Facebook, Google, and Microsoft exert a lot of influence over the developer community, with starry eyed developers eager to try the latest offerings. In the sometimes competitive platform landscape (iOS, Android, and cloud services such as Azure, GCE and AWS) as well as in an effort to attract talented developers, the large players often release open source platforms/frameworks to exert some leverage over the ecosystem. This can be somewhat evidenced by looking at the JavaScript frontend ecosystem, where many options with significantly overlapping purpose and design compete for adoption and mindshare. Competition comes at a cost of fragmentation and somewhat subverts efforts to standardize technologies in a vendor neutral, cross-cutting manner (e.g. web standards).

I recognize that evolution takes diversity and redundancy. I am just concerned about varying motives (both pragmatic and competitive), and for the overall health and cooperation of the open source community.

original_comment:
> Ah, it wasn't clear ay first glance that SFrame is part of Turi Create. With such a tight relationship between SFrame and Turi Create, will there also be pandas support?

As I mentioned, SFrame and Pandas data frames are already deeply compatible. The APIs working with SFrames allows us to push a lot of optimizations into the model creation process that would otherwise not be possible by using Pandas.

> At the risk of drifting off topic, what is the overlap between SFrame and pandas, and what are significant differences?

I tried outlining the key differences above. The overlap in terms of functionality is pretty high. The SFrame is pretty full featured and we plan to keep building on it and adding more things as we find gaps. The APIs are pretty similar so it should be quite natural to use them.

> Also, how does SFrame compare with the design goals and foundations of Dask? E.g.

Dask is another great project that we are aware of. It started around a year after the SFrame and at its core is a task scheduler that can help scale up Pandas using pure python primitives. It has some of the advantages of SFrame (parallelism, scale, interop with pandas etc.) but not all of them (can be extended to multiple languages, lazy evaluation, compression, interop with pandas etc.)

We have been actively developing the SFrame for over 4 years now. There are many reasons why we like SFrame.

- Its out of core so you can work with really large datasets
- Lazy evaluation lets you work interactively even on really large datasets
- Its fast! and has some awesome compression techniques that make sure you can do more with less
- Because it is written in C++, we can have support for multiple-languages in the future
- Its parallel

As for file paths (csv files to be loaded, saved sframe files and saved model files) - please note that all of the methods below accept any full or relative path you'll provide them:
```
sf = tc.SFrame.read_csv('some/path/some_file.csv')
sf.save('some/other/path/my_data.sf')
loaded_sf = tc.SFrame('some/other/path/my_data.sf')
model.save('new_desired_path/my_model.model`)
```

The current path your're running your python from doesn't matter - as long as you provide a valid path where you want sframes\models to be saved to or loaded from.

Also, it is not required to run your python script from within a specific path (`venv` or any other). 
 The only advice is to activate the virtualenv in which you've installed turicreate by running: `source ~/venv/bin/activate`.
After you do - feel free to write your own `.py` script or ipython notebook. Such script will usually begin with:
```
import turicreate as tc
data = tc.Sframe.read_csv('some_data.csv')
#...
model = tc.activity_classifier.create(data, ...)
#...
```

original_comment:
Thanks for taking an interest in the activity classifier!

Below is the piece of code used to produce `hapt_data.sframe` from the raw data found [here](http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/00341/HAPT%20Data%20Set.zip).
This follows the instructions in the README.txt file available with the raw data.

```python
from glob import glob
import turicreate as tc

def find_label_for_containing_interval(intervals, index):
    containing_interval = intervals[:, 0][(intervals[:, 1] <= index) & (index <= intervals[:, 2])]
    if len(containing_interval) == 1:
        return containing_interval[0]

# Load labels
labels = tc.SFrame.read_csv('./HAPT Data Set/RawData/labels.txt', delimiter=' ', header=False, verbose=False)
labels = labels.rename({'X1': 'exp_id', 'X2': 'user_id', 'X3': 'activity_id', 'X4': 'start', 'X5': 'end'})

# Load data
data = tc.SFrame()
acc_files = glob('./HAPT Data Set/RawData/acc_*.txt')
gyro_files = glob('./HAPT Data Set/RawData/gyro_*.txt')
files = zip(sorted(acc_files), sorted(gyro_files))
for acc_file, gyro_file in files:
    exp_id = int(acc_file.split('_')[1][-2:])
    user_id = int(acc_file.split('_')[2][4:6])
    
    # Load accel data
    sf = tc.SFrame.read_csv(acc_file, delimiter=' ', header=False, verbose=False)
    sf = sf.rename({'X1': 'acc_x', 'X2': 'acc_y', 'X3': 'acc_z'})
    sf['exp_id'] = exp_id
    sf['user_id'] = user_id
    
    # Load gyro data
    gyro_sf = tc.SFrame.read_csv(gyro_file, delimiter=' ', header=False, verbose=False)
    gyro_sf = gyro_sf.rename({'X1': 'gyro_x', 'X2': 'gyro_y', 'X3': 'gyro_z'})
    sf = sf.add_columns(gyro_sf)
    
    # Calc labels
    exp_labels = labels[labels['exp_id'] == exp_id][['activity_id', 'start', 'end']].to_numpy()
    sf = sf.add_row_number()
    sf['activity_id'] = sf['id'].apply(lambda x: find_label_for_containing_interval(exp_labels, x))
    sf = sf.remove_columns(['id', 'exp_id'])
    
    data = data.append(sf)

target_map = {
    1.: 'walking',          
    2.: 'climbing_upstairs',
    3.: 'climbing_downstairs',
    4.: 'sitting',
    5.: 'standing',
    6.: 'laying'
}

# Use the same labels used in the experiment
data = data.filter_by(target_map.keys(), 'activity_id')
data['activity'] = data['activity_id'].apply(lambda x: target_map[x])
data = data.remove_column('activity_id')

data.save('hapt_data.sframe')
```
